 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said Monday he hoped a date for a cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> could be set within 10 days, but said this would be only a first step toward resolving the 8-year-old war. In a televised interview, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said he wanted a cease-fire declared `` as soon as possible.'' He is scheduled to meet Wednesday with the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in separate talks on setting up a U.N.-supervised truce. `` The ceasefire is not an end in itself. It's the first very important step. We want a total solution of the problem,'' <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in the interview on <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The MacNeil-Lehrer News Hour.'' <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja </PERSON> <PERSON> Afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, said on the same program that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was continuing to use chemical warfare against his country, even though <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has said it is ready for an immediate suspension of the conflict. <PERSON> Ismat </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador, did not deny that his country had used chemical weapons but added that `` people should have learned by now not to take allegations by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> at their face value.'' `` We have said, and I ca n't go beyond that, that we will use every means available at our disposal to repel this aggression, this persistent aggression by the Iranians against our country,'' <PERSON> Kittani </P