<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     07-25 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Begins Test Aimed at Firing Space Shuttle Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A practice space shuttle countdown was under way here today in a test leading to a firing of Discovery's three main engines on the launch pad Saturday. The launch team started the count at 11:33 p.m. Sunday. On Wednesday, it planned to load more than a half million gallons of liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen propellant into the shuttle's external fuel tank It will be the first time a shuttle has been fueled since the Challenger explosion, which killed seven astronauts on Jan. 28, 1986. When the countdown reaches 10 seconds before a mock lift-off on Wednesday, a problem will be simulated to force a launch postponement. Then launch crews will rehearse what's called a 72-hour turnaround. They will empty the fuel tank, start another countdown, refill the tank and aim for a 20-second test firing of Discovery's main engines at 7:30 a.m. Saturday. The firing, with the shuttle bolted firmly on the pad, will check modifications made to the engines and is considered critical to Discovery being certified for the first post-Challenger shuttle flight. The launch, with a five-man crew, is scheduled for early September, but the date is in doubt as engineers continue to puzzle over how to fix a small gas leak in a steering engine system that is separate from the main engines. They hope to make the repair on the pad and avoid rolling Discovery back to a hangar, a move that could delay the flight as much as two months. Experts are considering several ways to reach the inaccessible leak, including cutting a hole through the shuttle's cargo bay wall and running a snake-like tube through the gas line in an effort to plug it. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said it will not make a decision on whether to move Discovery off the pad until after the main engine test firing.
</TEXT>
