<HEAD>Bush Proposes Child-Care Program, Starts Considering Running Mates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, after outlining a $ 2.2 billion child-care program designed to help close his gender gap with women, is turning his attention to selecting a running mate. The vice president says he expects to have `` some kind of a list'' of potential running mates prepared by sometime this week, although he hopes to delay announcing his choice until the GOP convention next month. The certain Republican presidential candidate was expected to spend much of this week mulling over his vice presidential selection and had few campaign events scheduled. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was drawing mixed reviews for his proposal for child-care tax credits of up to $ 1,000 per child for low-income families. For the neediest families _ those earning less than $ 10,000 a year _ the `` credit'' would become a direct government payment of the maximum $ 1,000 for each child of four or younger. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made the proposal Sunday in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> and Professional Women's Clubs in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, ending a five-day burst of campaigning in seven states. `` It was a gutsy move on the part of the vice president,'' said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON>, domestic affairs director for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s presidential campaign. The vice president's plan was a sharp departure from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's past policies on child care, and bears a price tag similar to a $ 2.5 billion Democratic plan now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The Democratic proposal chiefly sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., which Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ha