of former <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> rival, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, helped worked on the final draft of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s speech, according to her aides <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> said there was no discussion of the vice presidential selection process on the plane. The vice president told reporters that screening of potential running mates _ to look into backgrounds and financial histories _ would begin this week. Prospective candidates will be asked to fill out financial disclosure statements, he indicated. `` So by sometime next week, there will have to be some kind of a list,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told his <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> audience his `` Children's Tax Credit'' would range up to $ 1,000 per child under age 4 and would be `` refundable'' _ meaning families could receive something from the government even if they did n't earn enough to pay taxes. The vice president said the credit would be phased out as income rises. He gave no details on exactly how this would be done. Background information provided by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s staff said the tax credit would cost $ 1.5 billion a year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s four-point program also included: _ Expansion of the existing child-care tax credit to cover more low-income families, for a cost of $ 400 million a year _ Creation of workplace child-care centers for all government employees and a federally underwritten liability insurance program for private centers, $ 50 million a year _ More federal assistance to help states and local governments set up programs such as sick child care and before-and-after school care, $ 250 million
