<HEAD>Rivals Parley For Future Of Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BOGOR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sitting stiffly and avoiding eye contact, the leaders of four groups fighting for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> began their first talks today to try to fashion a political settlement. Their host, <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON>, said they would discuss such difficult issues as national reconciliation, forming a provisional government and building a neutral <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, which has been at war almost continuously since 1970. `` We of course realize that on these aspects ... there are divergences of views among you and that many years of conflict and contention have caused estrangment that may impede a quick convergence of positions,'' he said in an opening speech. <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON> said such a complex problem could n't be solved through a single meeting, but a solution will never be found unless a start is made to replace war with dialogue. The four Cambodian leaders gathered in a chandeliered room in the old palace of the late President <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> for informal `` cocktail party'' talks that have raised hopes for peace in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. In large easy chairs around a thick, circular table sat <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, prime minister of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s Vietnamese-installed government, and leaders of three guerrilla groups opposing him. They were <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samphan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, and Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON>, who is representing his father, Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>. As they gathered, three saffron-robed <ORGANIZATION> Cambodian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks who had traveled from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> filed into the palace to pray for success. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978 and by Western count maintains more than 100,000 troops there, was to meet the Cambodians in a second stage of talks in the afternoon. That meeting was also to be attended by <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s Communist ally, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>, and by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, which backs the guerrillas. At a photo session just before the morning talks, the leaders smiled at photographers and <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samphan </PERSON> waved, but they studiously avoided making eye contact with one another. Instead they gazed at huge Western-style oil paintings on the walls. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Senn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> have held two previous rounds of talks without success, and the current meeting represents the first gathering of all four <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> parties. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has never talked with the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance factions. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, meanwhile, was visiting <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> capital just 40 miles from <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION> but had no known plans to attend the talks. A Indonesian source said the former <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> monarch might make an appearance in <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION>, depending on progress in the talks. Earlier this month <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> resigned as president of the guerrilla coalition, charging the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> were killing his men. The tentative schedule called for two days of talks with the second day having the same format as the first _ the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> factions talking in the morning, then the Vietnamese and others joining in the afternoon. The talks are based on a July 1987 <LOCATION> Vietnam-Indonesia </LOCATION> agreement that calls for informal discussions to encourage the various antagonists to participate and allay <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s refusal to negotiate directly with the guerrillas. Disputes between <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> delayed the talks, which were not confirmed until the last minute. The association includes the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. Since 1970, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has suffered a devastating five-year civil war, a reign of terror by the Chinese-backed <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> from 1975 to 1978, a 1978 Vietnamese invasion and a continuing guerrilla war against the Vietnamese-backed government. Millions of people have been killed in the turmoil. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has announced it will withdraw 50,000 troops, or about half its force in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, this year and the rest by early 1990. Though Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> are allied with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> in a resistance coalition, they strongly distrust the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> because it killed hundreds of thousands of people when it ruled <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.
