<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTLE SHANNON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty drivers saddled up their buses for a 10th annual rodeo, as ribs and chicken sizzled on open-pit grills. The <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> rodeo was slower-moving than a Western counterpart, but competitors said it requires an equal amount of skill. `` A lot of people could n't drive a car through this course, let alone a 40-foot bus,'' driver <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillett </PERSON> said Sunday as he eyed the orange cones and barrels charting the course across the Castle <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> subway station parking lot, near <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. The buses lumbered through the cones, squashing some along the way. Judges in cowboy hats made notations on clipboards, and a country-western band played. Drivers were allowed seven minutes to steer their buses through the maze. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who hit the fewest cones in the fastest time, won. `` They do serpentines, three-point turns, backward parking and curbing the bus,'' said <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCourcy </PERSON>, an organizer. `` The rodeo allows them to show off their talent that most people take for granted.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It used to be that <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>' lottery millionaires could count on leaving their wallets home at least one day a year _ the day of the Millionaire's Reunion. But this year, after criticism that the lavish reunions were a waste of taxpayers' money, a thriftier affair is planned and the millionaires are getting stuck with some of the tab. The big money winners used to get lunch on a cruise ship, dinner and dancing at a classy spot and a night at a top hotel. At this year's reunion, on Aug. 19, they'll get beer, bratwurst and baseball _ and they'll have to pay for their own hotel rooms. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyc </PERSON>, a $ 3.8 million-winner from <LOCATION> Elk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, says he'll attend the luncheon, but skip the <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION> game, dinner and a special discount night at a Hyatt hotel. `` I thought the cost of last year's -LRB- reunion -RRB- was kind of exorbitant, but I'm conservative that way,'' Nyc said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nine ducklings and their parents lived it up at the swank <LOCATION> Ritz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION> where they swam in a Jacuzzi and dined on escargot, fresh lettuce, melba toast and bottled spring water served by white-gloved waiters. The ducklings were flown in from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> for a fund-raising re-creation Sunday of the 1941 children's book `` Make Way for Ducklings,'' which is set in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s Public Garden's pond. Children from a private elementary school in <LOCATION> Morganton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, flew in Saturday on a charter flight along with the <ORGANIZATION> ducks </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, an organizer of the event to raise money for the school. `` We visited <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> two years ago on a field trip and the children saw the ducks,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> said. `` They were very familiar with the book and that's when the idea for this project started.'' In the story, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> policeman befriends the ducks, which take up a residence in the pond. As <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> read from the book Sunday, about 200 people gathered around a sculpture that's near the pond and is dedicated to the story. The ducks, billed as the only known descendants of Mr. and Mrs. <PERSON> Mallard </PERSON> in <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McCloskey </PERSON>'s story, were taken in their cages to the pond and set free. Organizers hope to raise funds for an addition at the school through a $ 5-an-entry `` Name the Duck'' contest for the ninth duckling. In the story, there are just eight ducklings: <PERSON> Jack </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kack </PERSON>, Lack, <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nack </PERSON>, Ouack, Pack and Quack.
