<SECOND>PM-Drums and Bugles,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garfield Cadets Prepare to Defend World Title</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It takes more than 12 hours of practice a day under blazing sun or summer rain to get the precision right. But any student who wants to be in the Garfield Cadets Drum and <ORGANIZATION> Bugle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> knows that is the kind of summer $ 500 will buy. `` It's a lot like <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> boot camp,'' said 19-year-old <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Klophaus </PERSON>, a first-year corps member from <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. The 54-year-old corps, headquartered in the northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Garfield </LOCATION>, is made up of student musicians, ages 14 to 21, from across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The cadets are the current <ORGANIZATION> Drum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> champions. Next month, they will try for an unprecedented fifth DCI World Championship as they compete against 70 other corps in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Until then, the <PERSON> Garfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Cadets </PERSON>, who number about 100, will don their maroon and off-white uniforms and strut their stuff across eight states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as they complete the second half of their Summer 1988 tour. `` The biggest thing that makes them special is the type of training,'' said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON>, a visual instructor. `` It's very extreme.'' <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON>, 30, stands on the bleachers during practice to make sure the cadets' presentations are pleasing to the eye. `` The type of work and pressure they go through is similar to what someone in their age group would do when trying out for the Olympics,'' <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> said. `` The prestige of winning is ... like winning a gold medal.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, the group's executive director since 1982, said the corps challenges itself by purposely bypassing anything that might come easily in favor of the most difficult routines. `` If we know that we can do it, then we will not do it,'' <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said. A day at training camp in this northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> community begins at 7:30 a.m., when the corps rises, eats breakfast and starts practicing no later than 8:30. About 2:30 p.m., they eat again. They return to practice a half hour later. Dinner is served at 6:30 p.m., then the cadets are back at work for three more hours. They're free until lights out at 11, but often spend the time discussing improvements for the routine, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawrylko </PERSON>, a corps spokesman. All this, including bedding down on gymnasium floors, costs $ 500, which the cadets pay as a membership fee. `` I wanted to learn what hard work is and what it does to you,'' said first-year cadet <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Geltch </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Crossing, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` It's made me concentrate more.'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Poquis </PERSON>, a 20-year-old baritone horn player from <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said: `` I learned that no matter how downhill and exhausted you are, you can still push yourself that extra step. It builds character.'' Following the cadets from city to city is an 18-wheel truck that carries food and other supplies. Another 18-wheeler carries the instruments, along with the streamers and flags for the color guard. Four buses transport the cadets, vans carry instructors and support staff, and a 24-foot promotional bus tags along. Like most other drum and bugle corps, the <ORGANIZATION> Garfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadets </ORGANIZATION> raise money with cake sales, car washes, donations and raffles, along with membership fees. The corps has an annual budget of $ 450,000 to $ 500,000, said <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Pych </PERSON>, a member of the board of directors. This year, however, the cadets received their first corporate sponsorship, from K mart Stores and <ORGANIZATION> Emerson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Pych </PERSON> said. He said exact figures were not available. Besides becoming better musicians, the cadets are taught good competitive manners, <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> said. `` You never are a sore loser or an obnoxious winner,'' he said.
