<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes Said To End In Disputed Region, Though Some Fight On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ethnic Armenians in the disputed <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region went back to tending fields, driving buses and building homes today after their two-month strike failed to bring unity with <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, state-run media reported. An end to the latest strike in the predominantly Armenian enclave of the southern republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> would signal a step toward normalcy for an area in tumult since February. Still, a resident in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>'s capital, said some of the region's 162,000 people will press on with the annexation campaign. `` Today people went to work. Transport is operating and we have ended our strikes,'' reported the engineer for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. She declined to give her name. `` The situation is still very tense,'' she said by telephone. `` The decision has done little for us and we will continue this fight to the end. But what is the sense of continuing to strike?'' The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership decided a week ago that <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> will remain part of the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, which has ruled it since 1923. <PERSON> Nagorno-Karabh </PERSON>'s Armenians, predominantly Christian like their brethren in the neighboring Armenian republic, have waged a vocal campaign for annexation. They contend they suffer discrimination under the Azeris, most of whom are Moslem. The annexation drive was opposed by the Azerbaijani leadership, and the struggle over control of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> has fueled ethnic tensions in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION>. Mass demonstrations by Armenians in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> and the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> have drawn hundreds of thousands of people. And on Feb. 28, the unrest became violent when 26 Armenians and six other people were killed in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>. After <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s rejection of the annexation bid became known in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> last week, activists called for a five-day protest strike. But most residents heeded official warnings against prolonging the labor unrest. Strikes continued in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> through the weekend, but state-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> reported today that most workers in the region had decided to end the stoppage. Neither Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> nor the engineer reached in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> explained why residents decided to return to work, and other calls to the region did not go through. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Armenian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership met Sunday and that local officials were blamed for allowing the annexation drive to get out of hand. Party leaders said `` the situation that has shaped in the republic over the recent months has been a result of gross miscalculations and errors in the political, organizational and ideological work of party committees, of primary party organizations,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Adhering to the tougher stance against ethnic strife outlined by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in a speech a week ago, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the Armenian party leadership `` failed to sense the political danger of unjustifiable calls for revision of the existing national-territorial structure.'' Pravda, the party's central newspaper, also criticized Armenian party leaders who took up the cause of annexing the region, calling for review and rectification of their `` political immaturity.''
