<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parties that formed Prime Minister <PERSON> Prem </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinsulanonda </PERSON>'s last coalition government won 58 percent of the vote in a general election, but analysts predicted today that <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>'s probable return to power will be beset by discord `` The new government will face the same difficult problems it endured under <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>'s last administration because there is growing and open resentment of and opposition to <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>,'' said political scientist <PERSON> Somboon </PERSON> <PERSON> Suksamran </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chulalongkorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Since no pro-Prem party scored a majority in Sunday's polling, the next government will again have to be made up of several parties. In <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>'s last government, frictions among coalition partners proved troublesome. <PERSON> Somboon </PERSON> and other political analysts predicted that <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>, if he is returned to power, probably would not finish his four-year term without dissolving parliament or stepping down. <PERSON> Prem </PERSON> has served as prime minister since 1980, having dissolved parliament twice, survived two attempted coups and formed five different cabinets. A host of domestic pressures have been mounting, including weakened support from the powerful military, sharp criticism from opposition parties and recent labor and student protests. `` These pressures will only get more intense and will very likely force Prem to make big decisions on whether he should cling to his office,'' <PERSON> Somboon </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. But the head of Chart Thai -LRB- Thai Nation -RRB- Party, which polled the most votes in the country's 17th general election, said his party would support <PERSON> Prem </PERSON>'s continuation as prime minister. <PERSON> Chatichai </PERSON> <PERSON> Choonhavan </PERSON> told reporters today that a `` gentlemen's agreement'' had been made among the four coalition partners to back Prem The well-financed Chart Thai won 87 seats in the 357-seat <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> while coalition partners accumulated another 123. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> took 54; <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, 48; and Rassadorn -LRB- Citizens -RRB- Party 21 seats. The strongest parties and other power centers in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> in coming days are expected to engage in intense politicking and bargaining before the next coalition is forged and a prime minister named. The candidate who emerges must also be approved by <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s powerful constitutional monarch, <PERSON> Bhumibol </PERSON> <PERSON> Adulyadej </PERSON> Interior Minister <PERSON> Prachuab </PERSON> <PERSON> Soontrangkul </PERSON> announced that 16.9 million out of an eligible 26.6 million voters turned out for the election. The voting was marred by a grenade attack against a local politician in which two persons were killed and six others wounded. Officials also said Moslem separatists set fire to nine rural schools, a health clinic and a rest house in the southern province of <LOCATION> Narathiwat </LOCATION> in an apparent attempt to disrupt the elections. Some of the schools were used as polling stations. A total of 3,606 candidates from 16 political parties contested the seats in the lower house of Parliament. Among the opposition groups, the Prachakorn Thai -LRB- Thai Citizens -RRB- Party led with 31 seats and the newly formed <ORGANIZATION> Palang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dharma </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORG