<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar dropped sharply, then bounced back most of the way today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> for a net loss of 0.28 yen, while stocks slipped moderately lower. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ranged 1.65 yen between its high and low for the day, despite a lack of market-affecting news, traders said. `` Some participants, especially investment trusts, saw the dollar's decline in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last Friday ad began selling dollars in the morning, expecting it to go lower,'' said <PERSON> Masaharu </PERSON> <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON> of the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` But the market did n't go along with them.'' He said participants in the afternoon found themselves in dollar-short positions, and began buying back the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. The dollar opened at 130.85 yen, down 1.23 yen from Friday's close of 132.08 yen, and fell during the morning to as low as 130.20 yen It recovered to as high as 131.85 yen before closing at 131.80 yen, down 0.28 yen. Spot volume was estimated at $ 7.7 billion. On Friday, the dollar closed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 130.84 yen. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-share <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> dropped 117.81 points, or 0.43 percent, to finish the day's trading at 27,183.53. Volume on the market's first section was a light 650 million shares. Traders said many participants stayed on the sidelines because of uncertainty in the foreign exchange market and the upcoming release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures, expected Wednesday. The Nikkei index initially gained about 70 points, but retreated in the late morning. `` Depending on which direction the yen-dollar rate heads from the current 130-yen level, investors will start moving one way or the other,'' said <PERSON> Keiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishida </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION>. Traders said wild fluctuations in the market last week also had scared off some private investors. The Nikkei index plunged more than 600 points in last week's trading.
