<HEAD>Bus Crashes in N.J., Alabama, Leave 1 Killed, 69 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Bus crashes in two states took the life of one woman and injured 69 passengers, with the driver of one being charged with reckless driving and the other being praised for stopping his skidding bus from plunging into a ravine. A Colonial Trailways bus en route from Mobile to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sunday swerved to avoid a car apparently driving on the wrong side of a two-lane <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> highway. The bus skidded for about 30 feet after it overturned and came to a stop with the back of the bus in a shallow part of the ravine and the front jutting about 15 feet in the air. The accident, three miles south of <LOCATION> Camden </LOCATION> in southwestern <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, killed <PERSON> Rosie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulley </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> troopers, and left 34 other people injured. In <LOCATION> Edison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a charter bus driver was charged with reckless driving after his bus crashed into a bridge abutment, shearing off most of the roof and injuring 35 passengers who had just left a family reunion. One was still in critical condition this morning. Edison Police Sgt. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> said the bus, which originated in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, struck the abutment of a railroad bridge Sunday afternoon. The bus carried 46 passengers and the driver, <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> said. The driver, 43-year-old <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lassiter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was issued a summons for careless driving, <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lassiter </PERSON>, a driver for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION>, failed to observe a sign warning of low bridge clearance and was driving above the speed limit, he said. State Police Capt. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the driver of the bus involved in the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> accident said he had swerved to avoid an oncoming car. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said that was under investigation. State police spokesman <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said the bus was carrying 34 passengers and the bus driver. Four people were hospitalized overnight for observation. Passenger <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> sergeant, credited the driver for keeping the bus from plunging into the ravine. `` I thought the driver did an outstanding job in the way he handled the bus,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` It might have been a lot worse for us.''
