<HEAD>Future Looks Murky for Elusive Piglet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owner of a 40-pound pet piglet that eluded police for three hours until it paused for a handful of horse feed was told his porker may be killed if it is n't picked up within five days. But <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON>'s owner, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 32, will be in the <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Jail until at least Aug. 5, when he's scheduled to appear before a judge on a parole violation charge, his mother said. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was notified Saturday that the 8-month-old pig will be `` terminated'' if it is n't claimed in five days, said his mother, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. She said she would take the pig into her suburban home, but `` you know what the neighbors would say.'' She's hoping some farmer will come to the porker's rescue. <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON>'s brush with the law began Thursday when police stopped <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and a computer check showed he was wanted for violating probation on a charge of driving under the influence of alcohol. <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON> slipped out of <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s arms and made a clean getaway. Officer <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Yost </PERSON> and another officer spent the next few hours pursuing <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON> until a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> agricultural unit was called in for assistance. Deputy <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> `` Hi-Ho'' <PERSON> Hrabovsky </PERSON> used a handful of horse feed to stop and capture <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON>, who was sent off to a Sheriff's Office facility. Sheriff's Office spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinosa </PERSON> said he was not sure what the guidelines on animals called for, but he noted that in many livestock cases, the animals were kept for a specific time and then auctioned. `` The last thing I heard ... was that this was a pet, that we have his pet and that we would keep the pig until it is claimed,'' he said. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s mother said her son, who has always liked pigs, received <PERSON> Blackie </PERSON> from a friend as payment for a plumbing job. She said he intended to give the pig to relatives who live on a farm.
