<HEAD>Soviet Officer Predicts Collapse of Afghan Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS one graf to update with report on casualties since
pullout began.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet general says he doubts Afghan troops can survive when the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> withdraws from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He also predicts that Islamic fundamentalists will seize power. The statements by Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON>, who was once an adviser to the Afghans, represent a break with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s official line. In an interview with the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Ogonyok </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> says <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s ruling party is hopelessly disorganized, plagued by corruption and has bungled opportunities to make peace with insurgents. He also accuses the Soviet media of exaggerating Soviet and Afghan military victories. The interview appeared in the magazine's July 30 issue, which subscribers received Sunday. Western military and political analysts have said for some time they doubt the Afghan army can fight off U.S.-backed rebels on its own. They have predicted a collapse of the communist Afghan government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> after the Soviet pullout is completed next year. <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON>, who teaches philosophy at a military academy, is believed to be the first Soviet official to make similar predictions publicly. <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> has led the campaign for glasnost, or greater openness, on selected topics. The official Soviet line has held that Afghan government forces are well prepared to defend their country. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, commander of Soviet forces in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, told reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last month that the Afghan government has created an effective fighting force. Asked if he is confident Afghan forces can provide adequate defense from rebel attacks after a Soviet withdrawal, <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> told Ogonyok: `` If you judge the Afghan army by its current state, then I do n't have the confidence about which you speak.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began withdrawing its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> May 15. Under the terms of a U.N.-brokered accord, half of the more than 100,000 troops must be out by mid-August and the rest by Feb. 15. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Saturday that more than 35,000 soldiers have been withdrawn. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> is coming under increasing guerrilla artillery fire. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> says he is counting on the continued help of Soviet advisers for his 50,000 regular army troops after the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s forces are gone. He has said his forces can defend the country as long as outside assistance to the rebels is stopped. <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> noted that Afghan forces, even when backed by Soviet troops, have made little headway in capturing rebel-held territory. He said official Soviet press reports exaggerated military victories and suffered from a `` deficit of truth'' about how tough the combat was. The Aghan army is weak, he said, because the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the government lack popular support and have underestimated the threat of the armed opposition He recommended the government devote massive resources to building up the army. Asked what the situation would be like when the Soviet withdrawal is completed, he predicted `` activization of the Islamic factor.'' `` In the future, it's quite possible that Islamic fundamentalists will appear,'' he said. Some Afghan guerrillas want to establish an Islamic fundamentalist state. <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> said the Afghan leadership had been insensitive to religion and thereby alienated much of the population, drawing them to the opposition. He said <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s policy of national reconciliation, an attempt to bring opponents into the government, has failed even though internal opponents are tired of war, willing to engage in dialogue and hostile to the seven-party Afghan guerrilla alliance based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` This also can be considered a lost opportunity of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> leadership,'' <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> said. He said the ruling Afghan party is split into factions, pays little attention to people's needs and is plagued by bureaucracy and bribery. `` I fear that the disease of fractional battle and system of clans in the party has gone too far,'' <PERSON> Tsagolov </PERSON> said. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to help the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government fight the rebels. The <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> says 13,310 Soviet soldiers have been killed in the war, 35,500 have been wounded and more than 300 are missing in action. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported today that since May rebel forces have bombarded <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> with 178 rockets and 30 mines, killing 154 people and wounding 205 in the Afghan capital.
