<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police today shot and killed a former army officer who escaped from prison while serving a life sentence in the assassination of President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, the government announced. <PERSON> Essam </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Kemary </PERSON>, 37, a former major, was killed in a hail of gunfire when police attacked an apartment he and two other fugitives used as a hideout, an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement said. Two police officers were wounded when the police gunfire was returned with a volley of bullets and explosive charges from the hideout. Both officers were reported in satisfactory condition in a hospital, the ministry statement said. It was not clear whether the two other fugitives _ <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamis </PERSON>, 40, and <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Aswani </PERSON>, 31 _ escaped before police stormed the apartment in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>'s el-Sharabiya district. In the apartment, the ministry said, police found plastic bombs. A ministry spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said security forces were searching for the two other fugitives. Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said el-Kemary was `` by far the most dangerous'' of the three escapees. The dawn attack ended a nationwide manhunt that the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> launched after el-Kemary and the two others, also serving life sentences in <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s killing, escaped July 17 from the maximum-security Tura jail on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. In the dawn jailbreak, the three men forced open their prison cell with an iron bar and overpowered the guards, seizing their rifles and knocking one man unconscious. The fugitives then shot their way out of the prison to a getaway car, police said. According to the government, the three men were members of a Moslem fundamentalist group known as Jihad, or Holy War. Jihad was blamed for <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s slaying at a military parade on Oct. 6, 1981, and a subsequent coup attempt. <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s assassination sparked a security crackdown on Moslem extremists. After a series of trials, three convicted assassins were executed by firing squad, another two were hanged and more than 120 men were given prison terms up to life. El-Kemary, <PERSON> Khamis </PERSON> and el-Aswani were convicted of planning the assassination and the coup attempt, in addition to membership in an armed group _ <LOCATION> Jihad </LOCATION> _ trying to disrupt the public order. The three did not actually shoot at <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>.
