<HEAD>Pinochet Expected To Be Single Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s four top military commanders will meet Aug. 30 to pick the candidate for the presidential referendum later this year, the government announced today. President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, 72, the right-wing military commander who has ruled <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> since coming to power in a 1973 coup, is widely expected to be the lone candidate. It will be the first presidential voting in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> since 1970, when <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist, was elected. He died in the coup led by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. The presidential nomination is to be made by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the army commander, and by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> chief Gen. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> commander Adm. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Toribio </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON>, and national police chief <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stange </PERSON>. The nomination, based on a 1980 military-drafted Constitution, must be unanimous and made within 48 hours. If the four commanders disagree, the candidate is to be chosen by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, made up of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the four-member military junta and the presidents of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>. The latter is a Pinochet-appointed official. The Constitution mandates that the vote be held within 30 to 60 days after the nomination of the candidate. <PERSON> Matthei </PERSON> said last week that the date for the vote has been set, but he would not disclose it. The vote is widely expected to be held in the first week of October, according to unofficial reports. In the voting, Chileans will only be able to vot `` yes'' or `` no'' on the candidate. If he wins approval, the candidate will serve an eight-year term starting March 11, 1989. If he is rejected by voters, a multi-candidate election will be held in 1990, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in power until then.
