<HEAD>Drought Has Trout Farmers Rushing From Hatcheries To Streams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Weeks of dry, hot weather are forcing the state's four trout farms into a race with drought as workers rush to transfer fish from too-warm hatching troughs to cooler streams before they die. `` The warmer the water the less oxygen the water has, and we have trouble keeping them alive,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ort </PERSON>, a worker at the state's <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> Fish Hatchery in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>. `` We'd rather give the fishermen their fish a month early rather than keep them.'' Because of the summer drought, the state <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> must finish stocking 600,000 fish in streams, lakes and rivers by the end of July, a month earlier than usual, officials say. Already, the water in <LOCATION> Armstrong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, which feeds into fish-hatching troughs at the <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> hatchery, has topped 70 degrees three times this month, <PERSON> Ort </PERSON> said. Water levels in the creek have dropped as well, forcing <PERSON> Ort </PERSON> to allow seven of his 20 ponds to dry up. Most of western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s 2,000 miles of trout streams, lakes and rivers must be stocked by the commission to maintain the popular sport of trout-fishing. The state's trout-stocking program breeds the fish and raises them from eggs to a catchable size _ 8 inches or longer when the fish are about 18 months old, officials say. Once in the state's rivers and streams, most trout are caught within a week or two, said <PERSON> Mallory </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a production coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>. `` I would expect the catch to be higher than usual because the water levels have been so low the fish do n't have a place to escape to,'' Ms. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said.
