<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Arab assailants today stoned an Israeli army jeep in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, forcing the jeep to veer off the road and turn over, the army said. Four military police were injured. The incident occurred several hours after the army freed 148 Palestinian prisoners from <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> as a goodwill gesture to Moslems on the four-day Eid al-Adha holiday, or `` Feast of the Sacrifice.'' An army spokesman said the jeep carrying green-uniformed border patrol guards was stoned as it patrolled the Jabaliya refugee camp. The driver was injured in the hand and veered off the road, said the spokesman, who could not be identified in accordance with army regulations. Three other police suffered minor injuries and two of them were taken to a hospital, he said. Arab news reports said soldiers immediately clamped a curfew on the camp, banning more than 60,000 residents from leaving their homes. The army today freed 148 Palestinians from the <LOCATION> Ketziot </LOCATION> tent prison in the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> desert, a spokesman said. He said some had been jailed without trial and the rest were serving short sentences for crimes linked to the Palestinian uprising. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said more than 3,000 Palestinian detainees would remain in <LOCATION> Ketziot </LOCATION>. The army said it held more than 5,000 Palestinian prisoners in <LOCATION> Ketziot </LOCATION> and other prisons. The prisoners' release came a day after confrontations in the occupied territories left two Palestinians dead and six wounded, raising to 233 the Arab death toll since the uprising began Dec. 8. Four Israelis have also died. Seven cities and refugee camps in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> remained under curfew today after the clashes, the army said. The unrest was partly triggered by coinciding Jewish and Moslem holidays. The Moslem feast marks when the biblical patriarch <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> was ordered by <PERSON> God </PERSON> to sacrifice his son, <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON>. The Jewish commemoration marks the destruction of a <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> temple by Roman rulers nearly 2,000 years ago. A holiday custom calls for the Moslems to visit cemeteries and leaders of the uprising called on their followers to visit the graves of Arabs slain during the uprising. In an unprecedented ruling Sunday, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld an army decision to temporarily occupy a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> home so soldiers could oversee a highway that has been the scene of numerous stoning attacks on Israeli vehicles. Court spokesman <PERSON> Shmaryahu </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the ruling appeared to be the first time the court had allowed soldiers to take over an <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> house for security purposes. In the past, the army has confiscated, wrecked or sealed homes belonging to Palestinians suspected of involvement in anti-Israeli violence. <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> radio said soldiers have wrecked or sealed up 52 Palestinian homes since December. The ruling was one of a series of decisions since the uprising began in which the court has consistently upheld measures of the Israeli military authorities.
