<HEAD>Forest Fire in Southern Yugoslavia Brought Under Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A blaze that raged for eight days and destroyed more than 10,000 acres of forests near the <LOCATION> Yugoslav-Greek </LOCATION> border has been brought under control, media reports said Monday. The fire occurred in the <LOCATION> Valandovo </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> several miles north of the frontier with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The blaze was started by a farmworker who did not extinguish a cigarette, a newspaper reported. It eventually was subdued by thousands of firefighters, soldiers and local inhabitants, with help from three air force water bombers. The intense temperatures from the fire set off explosions in a World War II minefield, but no one was hurt, reports said. <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> have been hit by a protracted heat wave that has sparked other forest fires.
