<TEXT>
 A white university student who refused to do cumpulsory military service on the grounds he would be `` defending racism'' was sentenced Monday to six years in prison. Magistrate P.H. <PERSON> Bredenkamp </PERSON> imposed the maximum penalty on <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> for his refusal to undergo the military training required of all white males in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` The consequences of your imprisonment are in you own hands,'' <PERSON> Bredenkamp </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON>, 25. `` You have had the opportunity ... to provide a useful service to the public.'' The training involves two years of initial service. Afterward, men are subject to annual military call-ups that can last as long as three months. `` My view of the South African <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is that it is not a peace-keeping force but that its basic function is that of upholding and defending racism,'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> said last week at his trial. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> declined to request a non-combat posting, which sometimes is granted to men who object to military training on religious grounds. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> refused to serve for moral and political reasons, saying he strongly opposed the government's apartheid policies of racial segregation. The government does not release statistics on how many white men refuse to serve in the military.
