<FIRST>r i AM-China-Prices     07-25 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Prices,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Boosts Cigarette, Liquor Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Monday announced sharp price increases for cigarettes and liquor, but also said inflation-battered consumers will be spared further increases this year. Yuan Mu, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, or cabinet, said the prices of famous brand cigarettes and spirits will be allowed to float as of Tuesday, putting an end to government-fixed, and generally arbitrarily low, prices. Yuan said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> had decided not to carry out any other price reforms this year to curb inflation, which has been rising at an alarming rate since the beginning of 1988, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said last week that consumer prices in June were 19 percent higher than in the same month in 1987, compared to an inflation rate of 7.2 percent for all of last year. The government earlier this year raised the prices of eggs, vegetables, pork and sugar as part of reforms aimed at ending state controls over prices and allowing the value of goods to be determined by market forces. The elimination of government controls has caused the prices of some goods to soar as the inefficient economy fails to keep up with rising demand. Black market dealings and hoarding of goods still sold at government-set prices have also boosted prices. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Changbi </PERSON>, an official of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prices </ORGANIZATION>, as saying the prices of famous brand cigarettes could go up between 15 and 290 percent after they are allowed to fluctuate. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said the price for a bottle of `` <LOCATION> Maotai </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous and sought-after spirit, will jump from $ 5.40 to $ 32.40. Yuan said the price increases for choice cigarettes and wines will have little social impact `` because most buyers are government organizations and those individuals with high incomes.'' But <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said the price of B-grade cigarettes will also be boosted by 13.4 percent and all alcohol made from grain will go up in price by 20 percent. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> uses 14 million tons of grain a year to make beer and other alcohol, and the government has said this is a luxury the nation ca n't afford when it is struggling to produce enough grain just to keep its 1 billion people fed. Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> and other reform-minded leaders in recent months have emphasized that price reform is risky but inevitable if <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is to modernize its economy and end the heavy financial burden of price subsidizing. The government has put off decontrolling prices, partly because of mounting public discontent over the rising cost of living. The Politburo, the party's supreme decision-making body, announced in June that systematic plans for price reform were being drawn up. Senior officials said the program would take three to five years to carry out. Yuan said price adjustments will resume Jan. 1, 1989, when newspapers, which have been hit by jumps in the price of newsprint, will cost more. He did not say what the increase would be. Yuan said the rise in the cost of cigarettes should curb speculation and profiteering that has thrived under the current pricing system. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is the world's biggest cigarette producer and consumer, turning out 228 billion cigarettes a year for its 300 million smokers.
</TEXT>
