<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Delegate Says Ne Win Resignation Accepted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with party delegate saying
congress accepted Ne Win's resignation but rejected his call for
referendum on one-party rule. Pick up 2nd pvs, The three-day...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A special ruling party congress today accepted the resignation of strongman Ne Win but rejected his call for a referendum that could have ended 26 years of one-party rule, a congress delegate said. Official <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, however, said only that Ne Win's resignation had been debated by the delegates and did not indicate what action, if any, was reached The delegate, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> agreed to accept the resignations of Ne Win as party chief and <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> as the vice chairman, but to retain them as `` inactive members.'' Burmese analysts suggested that the vagueness of the official radio broadcast reflected divisions within party ranks. The broadcast said the 1,061 party delegates empowered the party's central committee to evaluate a sweeping proposal for economic reform. But it gave no indication of whether any of the new measures had been accepted. The three-day congress of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been considering dramatic changes in a state-controlled economic system that turned a potentially prosperous country into a debt-ridden, poverty-stricken nation. The key architect of the system, <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, tendered his resignation Saturday as chairman of the party and offered to remove himself from political life. Five other top leaders likewise submitted resignations. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> announced Sunday that an emergency session of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> would convene Wednesday, apparently to act on Ne Win's proposal of holding a referendum on whether <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> should scrap a quarter century of one-party rule in favor of a multi-party system The emergency session could also deal with the appointment of new government leaders to replace the five who are resigning. The five, including President <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yu </LOCATION>, held government posts in addition to their party positions. Prime Minister <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Kha </PERSON>, one of the few top leaders not on the resignation roll, was expected to be named today to replace the 77-year-old Ne Win as chairman of the ruling party. The sudden and generally unexpected changes come in wake of bloody anti-government riots and worsening economic conditions in the isolationist Southeast Asian nation. The official radio, broadcasting from the congress, carried speeches of several among the more than 1,000 delegates asking Ne Win to reconsider his retirement `` until success has been achieved.'' Indeed, some Western diplomats doubt that Ne Win _ who has held undisputed power for 26 years _ will desist from interference in the future party and the organization of the new government. Not only did the former military chief, who seized power in a 1962 coup, crush anti-government opposition that occasionally flared. He also moved against leaders within his own ranks when they exhibited too much promise and independence. This has left a leadership vacuum in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> that may prove difficult to fill if there is a wholesale removal of officials from party and government ranks, as Ne Win indicated. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Kha </PERSON>, who assumed the prime ministership in 1977, has to date not exhibited any particular dynamism or vision that would be necessary to implement the wide-ranging reforms being debated by the congress. In a speech on Sunday, party general secretary <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON> admitted that economic production had declined, working skills have deteriorated and `` losses and wastages can not be controlled effectively.'' `` Because of these weaknesses and as a result of adverse repercussions from the world economic conditions today, the state economic situation is declining,'' he said. <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON> called for cutting most state involvement in agriculture, mining, fisheries, industry, transportation and other economic sectors. He also called for allowing private joint ventures between Burmese entrepreneurs and foreign investors, something Ne Win outlawed shortly after seizing power. Since October, student-led demonstrations have erupted three times in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and the unrest spread to other cities. Martial law continues in <LOCATION> Prome </LOCATION>, 180 miles north of the capital, where there were riots last week. Last month, at least 50 people died in anti-government unrest.
</TEXT>
