<FIRST>u a AM-Poll-SpaceProgram Bjt   07-25 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Space Program, Bjt,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Americans Favor Space Station, Mars Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans believe the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has lost its edge in space exploration and favor initiatives including a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space station and manned flights to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General-Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> poll has found. A sizable share of the respondents in the national poll said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was doing too little in space exploration. As well as backing new efforts, a majority expressed support for the space shuttle program. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> plans to resume shuttle launches in September, more than 2 -LCB- years after the shuttle Challenger exploded during takeoff, killing the seven astronauts aboard. However, equipment problems may delay the launch. Nearly half of the 1,223 adults surveyed said the shuttle explosion had shaken their confidence in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, and 60 percent of that group said their faith in the space agency has not been restored. That means that about 30 percent of all respondents lacked confidence in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. Still, when asked to rate its overall effectiveness, 58 percent said it has done a good or excellent job while 37 percent said only fair or poor. About half the respondents said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s budget should remain the same, and 30 percent said it should be increased. Despite concerns over the federal deficit, only 18 percent said the space budget should be decreased. And of those who wanted <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s budget increased, 74 percent said they would be willing to pay higher taxes to accomplish it. In another indication of general support for space projects, 40 percent said the nation was doing too little in exploring space and 36 percent said it was doing about enough. Just about a fifth said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was doing too much in space exploration. There was a striking split between the sexes, with men far more likely than women to favor space programs. Fifty-six percent of men said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was doing too little in space exploration; only a quarter of women agreed. Forty-one percent of men supported increasing the space exploration budget, compared to just 19 percent of women. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> 30 years ago to pursue civilian exploration of space, but in recent years it increasingly has handled military payloads as well. That was opposed by a slim plurality in the survey: Forty-eight percent said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> should be involved in non-military projects only, while 41 percent approved including military work. The split was narrowly outside the poll's margin of error of plus or minus three percentage points. Fewer than a quarter of respondents said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is ahead of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in space exploration, while the remainder were split on whether the Soviets are ahead or the two countries are about even. At the same time, there was sentiment for superpower cooperation in space. About half of those polled favored last month's proposal by the Soviets for a U.S.-Soviet joint effort to send astronauts to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. An additional 15 percent said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should work alone to reach Mars. Taken together, 64 percent favored some program to land astronauts on Mars, while 30 percent were opposed. The rest had no opinion. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has no program to send astronauts to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. It is seeking funding for a space station, but the $ 200 million approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this month is only enough to phase out the program or put it on hold. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had approved $ 700 million and a joint committee is to resolve the issue. The goal of a space station was supported by 55 percent, with 34 percent opposed. On the soon-to-be resumed space shuttle program, 40 percent said efforts should be expanded and the same number said work should continue at the same level. Fewer than a fifth said the shuttle program should be cut back. The Media General-AP poll consisted of telephone interviews June 22-July 2 with a randomly selected sample of 1,223 adults across the nation. <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a communications company based in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the Tampa -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION> -RRB-. Tribune and the <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- Journal, and operates TV stations <ORGANIZATION> WXFL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, WCBD in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> WJKS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
