<FIRST>r a AM-PollMethod     07-25 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll Method,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Space Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General-Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> poll is based on telephone interviews June 22-July 2 with 1,223 adults in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The phone numbers were selected randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult in each household who had the most recent birthday. The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning that if every adult American were asked the same questions, the results theoretically would be within three points of the poll's results, 19 times out of 20. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five points, for example, for those who want the budget for space exploration to be increased. There are other sources of potential error in polls, including the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and responses in this poll; because of rounding, some totals may exceed 100: 1. In general, do you think the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is doing too much in space exploration right now, or too little, or about enough? Too much: 19 percent. Too little: 40 percent. About enough: 36 percent. Do n't know or no answer: 5 percent. 2. Do you think the space shuttle program should be expanded, cut back, or kept at the same level? Expanded: 40 percent. Cut back: 17 percent. Same level: 40 percent. DK-NA: 3 percent. 3. Do you think the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should build a space station, or not? Yes: 55 percent. No: 34 percent. DK-NA: 12 percent. 4. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has suggested a joint program with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to land astronauts on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. Do you think the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should try to land astronauts on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> by itself, or should it undertake a joint program with the Soviets, or should the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> not try to land astronauts on <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> at all? By itself: 15 percent. Joint program: 49 percent. Not at all: 30 percent. DK-NA: 7 percent. 5. Do you think the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's budget for the overall space program should be increased, decreased, or kept at the same level? Increased: 30 percent. Decreased: 18 percent. Same level: 48 percent. DK-NA: 5 percent. a. If increased: Would you be willing to pay higher taxes for the increase? Yes: 74 percent. No: 20 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent. 6. Who do you think is ahead in the exploration of space _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, or do you think they are about equal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>: 23 percent. Soviets: 31 percent. Even: 37 percent. DK-NA: 20 percent. 7. How would you rate the overall effectiveness of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautic </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> _ excellent, good, only fair or poor? Excellent: 10 percent. Good: 45 percent. Only fair: 30 percent. Poor: 7 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent. 8. Do you think <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> should be involved in military and non-military projects in space, or should it be involved only in non-military projects? Both: 41 percent. Only non-military: 48 percent. DK-NA: 11 percent. 9. The space shuttle program was set back when the shuttle Challenger exploded in 1986, killing the seven astronauts aboard. Looking back, did that accident shake your confidence in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, or not? Yes: 47 percent. No: 50 percent. DK-NA: 3 percent. 11. If yes: How about now _ has your confidence in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> been restored, or not? Yes: 34 percent. No: 60 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent.
</TEXT>
