<SECOND>AM-China-Women,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Issues Regulations to Protect Women Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Monday issued regulations forbidding job discrimination against women and guaranteeing them healthy work environments. The State Council, or Cabinet, also said employers can not reduce the wages or annul women's contracts during periods of pregnancy, maternity leave or nursing. The regulations, to go into effect Sept. 1, extended maternity leave from 56 to 90 days, and stipulate that women who have difficult deliveries will have an option of another 15 days. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s constitution guarantees equality between the sexes, but in reality <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> women face various kinds of educational and job discrimination. Women university graduates have much more difficulty finding suitable jobs than men, women's wages are often lower, and factory managers with newly won powers to dismiss workers have fired women in larger numbers than men. In the countryside, many girls are forced by custom and parents to quit school even before completing the compulsory nine years so they can work in the fields or in factories. Women frequently also work in small and often unsafe mines, although past laws, and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> regulations, state that women are not allowed to engage in underground mining or heavy labor unsuited to the individual's health. The regulations urge employers with a large staff of women to provide appropriate sanitary equipment, rooms for pregnant women to rest, and nurseries and kindergartens. <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said, without providing details, that violators of the regulations or those who infringe on the rights of women workers will be punished.
