<FIRST>u i AM-SwingingBritain Bjt   07-25 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swinging Britain, Bjt,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>In The '80s, England Still Swings Like the '60s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you thought the'60s were swinging, just look at the'80s. According to a statistical study published Monday, the sexual permissiveness associated with the 1960s is tame stuff compared with the 1980s _ AIDS and yuppie puritanism notwithstanding The `` Swinging'60s'' were invented largely by British pop musicians, fashion designers and hairstylists, so it was appropriate that the study came from a British independent research office, the Family Policy Studies Center. It reported that the divorce rate has jumped from 2.1 per 1,000 marriages in 1961 to 12.9 in 1986; illegitimate births are up from 6 percent to 21 percent; births are down from 17.9 per 1,000 to 13.3; and teen-age brides are down from 28 percent to 14 percent. It says that between 1960 and 1964, only one in 100 first-time brides under age 25 lived with their partners before marrying them. Twenty years later, the figure is almost one in four, the study says. Figures for bridegrooms do not appear in the government statistics used in the study, according to its editor, <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Henwood </PERSON>. The report says the figures suggest a much more liberal attitude in the 1980s toward childbirth out of wedlock. Not only has illegitimacy more than trebled, but the mothers apparently feel much less compulsion to marry before giving birth, while the fathers are more likely to acknowledge paternity. The study said 38 percent of birth certificates for illegitimate children bore the names of both parents in 1961. In 1986, the figure had risen to 66 percent, it said. `` The paradox of the 1960s may be less of a puzzle than it first appears,'' the report concludes. `` It is, after all, the people who grew up in, or were living through, the 1960s who are now making their appearance in many of the cohabitation, illegitimacy, marriage and divorce statistics. The class of'68 has come of age.'' `` The swinging'60s do seem a bit of mythical when we look at the facts and figures, but it really depends on the image of'60s,'' Ms. <PERSON> Henwood </PERSON> said in an interview. At 30, she admits to having no firsthand experience of the `` Swinging'60s,'' but knows they were `` a period of great change _ music, clothing and politics ... We look back and assume it was a time of free love, communes, that sort of thing. In fact, what made the image was a few notorious figures living in permissive relationships, but their values were not shared by most people at the time.'' The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> asked some leading figures of the'60s what they thought of the study. `` The ` Swinging'60s' took their name from the music, not the morality,'' said actor <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Stamp </PERSON>, who made his name playing the title role in the 1962 film version of `` <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>.'' `` Compare <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> to <PERSON> Jimi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> and the Pet Shop Boys to the Beatles. There you have the essential difference between the'60s and the'80s,'' Stamp was quoted as saying. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrimpton </PERSON>, the model who made the miniskirt famous, was quoted as saying: `` I never had a swinging mentality. I wore short skirts but I was a commodity of the'60s. It was other people who were making things happen. I just happened to be there.'' And cartoonist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Steadman </PERSON> was quoted as saying: `` The permissive society was about lots of things, not just sex. We were willing to buck authority ... Now life is getting more and more standardized and barren, and there is a backlash spurred by AIDS, a reformist influence which does rather tend to concentrate the mind.''
</TEXT>
