<HEAD>First Graduates of Tibet University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s only comprehensive institute of higher learning on Friday awarded diplomas to the remote mountain region's first university graduates, it was reported Monday The official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said 246 students graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Tibet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, with 74 receiving bachelor's degrees in literature, law and philosophy. The university, located in the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, was established in 1985 as <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s first full university. The region also has a teacher's college. The university's 778 students are enrolled in eight departments, and 14 of its 17 professors and associate professors are of Tibetan nationality, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> said. The <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government has tried to aid <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most impoverished and least developed areas, by building schools, hospitals and roads and providing funds for industry Relations between Tibetans and non-Tibetan Chinese remain strained by a long history of confrontations climaxing in the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, when leftists persecuted many Tibetans and tried to suppress Tibetan religion and language. Last fall and again in March crowds led by <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks staged anti-Chinese, pro-independence riots, but <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> insists they represented a small minority of Tibetans and that the lives of Tibetans have improved markedly under communist rule.
