<HEAD>Volcker Says World Bank May Wither Away Unless U.S. Contributes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> may wither away as the biggest source of aid to the Third World unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acts soon to pledge a new contribution, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, warned on Monday. The bank, headed by <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, a former congressman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, wants a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pledge of $ 70.1 million a year over the next six years for an increase in its capital. So far, 140 of the 151 governments that own the bank have decided to contribute. Among the other countries that have not made a pledge are <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has urged approval of the contribution. It has been held up in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by disagreement over what should be done to handle the bulk of the Third World's $ 1.2 trillion debt. Last year the bank got back more in repayments and interest from Third World borrowers than it gave them in new loans. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> officials want to reverse that trend and increase lending to well over $ 20 billion a year in the early 1990s. `` Our influence and leadership within the bank are certainly at stake, and I would raise the question ... if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is not going to participate in capital increases ... whether the bank itself can survive over a long period of time,'' <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON> told a news conference. He added that the bank could continue lending for a year or two without new capital. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as the biggest shareholder, is expected to furnish more than 18 percent. `` But against the prospect of not getting their capital replenished, it is not in the nature of the beast and would not be responsible for them to continue lending at that rate of speed in the face of a vote of no-confidence by their major shareholders,'' said <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>, who left the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> last year. A contribution has been endorsed by former presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. Last week they were joined by nine former secretaries of the treasury. A group of supporters, the <ORGANIZATION> Bretton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, is seeking statements of backing from the major presidential candidates.
</TEXT>
