<HEAD>Man Executed for Taking Bribes for Color TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man was executed Monday after being convicted of taking bribes from companies speculating in much-coveted color television sets, according to an official report. The <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yonghong </PERSON> was executed for receiving about $ 32,400 to help work units obtain color TVs. <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON>, an employee of the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, in one instance was given the equivalent of $ 10,800 for selling 200 color TVs to a company. The demand for color TVs far exceeds supply, and profiteers able to obtain sets can sell them on the black market for far more than government-set retail prices. <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON>, 35, was arrested in September 1985 and sentenced to death in March 1987. He appealed the verdict, but the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last month upheld the lower court's ruling. The government has called for police and courts to deal harshly with the rising number of economic criminals such as speculators, profiteers and embezzlers. Execution in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is usually by bullet to the back of the head.
