<HEAD>Virgin Islanders Observe Hurricane Supplication Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s 11,000 public employees took the day off Monday for Hurricane Supplication Day, the day residents pray they wo n't get hit by a hurricane. Hurricane Supplication Day, which marks the traditional start of the hurricane season for the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island group, is one of 25 holidays <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> observe each year. Another is Hurricane Thanksgiving Day, on Oct. 17, traditionally the last day of the hurricane season and a day set aside for giving thanks for sparing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory from the storms. Even though the islands' civil defense service recognizes the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, which runs from June 30 to Nov. 30, islanders still observe the traditional hurricane holidays. All government offices except for essential services such as hospitals and the police and fire departments were closed on the three islands of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Croix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomas </LOCATION> and <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s. Banks and stores stayed open, however, and most people went about their business as usual. Although the religious significance of the holiday is sometimes lost, <ORGANIZATION> Holy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Christiansted </LOCATION> held two hurricane supplication services Monday. `` We had a lot of people at the second one,'' a receptionist said. <PERSON> Elroy </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Territorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said the islands have not been hit by a major hurricane since the 1950s.
