<HEAD>Cambodian Factions Meet For First Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s warring parties held peace talks Monday for the first time, but they apparently made no progress on negotiating an end to the country's civil war. The two central problems to be tackled are the future of the communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas and organizing elections for a new Cambodian government. `` Although we have not solved any concrete problems, each side has revealed its position to the other side, `` said Cambodian Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> after talks with the three guerrilla groups, which oppose his Vietnamese-installed government. The four Cambodian leaders gathered in the summer palace of the late President <PERSON> Sukarno </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION>, a mountain retreat 37 miles outside <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, for the so-called `` cocktail party'' of the factions. `` This is a very preliminary stage,'' said <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON>, who organized the meeting. On Monday, <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> met with guerrilla leaders <PERSON> Khieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Samthan </PERSON> of the communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> and Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranariddh </PERSON>, who represented his father Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>. The four later were joined by representatives of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, its close ally <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and the foreign ministers of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION> _ which is the main backer of the guerrillas. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in 1978 and by Western count maintains more than 100,000 troops there, says it has withdrawn several thousand soldiers. It has announced it will pull out 50,000 troops this year and the rest by early 1990. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> told reporters he presented a seven-point proposal for a political settlement in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The plan contains mostly positions that already had been rejected by the guerrillas. It calls for maintaining the status-quo in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> until elections are organized to form a new government. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> has said he can not accept the guerrillas' demand that he dissolve his government before the elections. Instead, he said he proposed forming a `` ntional reconciliation council'' headed by <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> to implement any peace agreements and organize the elections. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> resigned July 10 as the president of the guerrilla coalition because he said the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> were killing his men. He arrived in <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> on Saturday as a guest of President <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON>, but said he would not attend the <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION> talks. The prince is considered the central figure in a settlement and future government, and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said the leaders of all four factions would meet him in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> in the next few days. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> also demanded the dissolution of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the largest of the guerrilla forces. `` Only by eliminating the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> ... can we eliminate the possibility of the <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> regime returning to <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> said. From 1975 until <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded, the fanatical <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime of Prime Minister Pol Pot killed hundreds of thousands of people. Diplomats say the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> is storing arms for attacks after the Vietnamese troops leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The meeting represents the first gathering of the four Cambodian parties. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> held two rounds of unsuccessful talks since 1987, but <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has never met with the factions of the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> resistance. Asked if he was happy with the talks, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s delegate, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> said, `` I am optimistic. I do n't say happy, but optimistic. Three Buddhist monks from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> chanted prayers for the success of the talks outside the Dutch colonial palace where the meetings were held. <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON> said the meeting is to continue Tuesday and would last `` as long as it takes.'' The tentative schedule called for two days of talks.
