<HEAD>Former Illinois Congressman Who Voted for Nixon Impeachment Dies
at 80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> McClory </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> reluctantly thrust into the national spotlight for his role in impeachment proceedings against President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, is dead at age 80. <PERSON> McClory </PERSON>, who represented the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburbs in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for 20 years until 1982, collapsed at church Sunday and died a short time later at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, his wife, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON>, said Monday. `` He went out jogging, got a paper and then came back to go with me to church. Everything was fine,'' Mrs. <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> said. `` Then it happened. He just collapsed and never came out of it.'' <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> was the second-ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> during congressional hearings on the break-in at the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in the Watergate complex in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Although he was a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> loyalist, <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> was one of the leading House supporters of an article of impeachment in 1974 charging <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> with abusing his constitutional powers in the Watergate matter. He drafted another article charging the president with contempt of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for resisting subpoenas. `` I feel really torn,'' <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> said in an interview at the time. `` But I'm disassociating this job from my relationship with the president on philosophy and policies.'' During the impeachment hearings, <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> said he was not convinced that <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was directly involved in the Watergate coverup but rejected suggestions that he had a partisan obligation to defend the president against all of the accusations. `` I have heard it said by some that they can not understand how a Republican could vote to impeach a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president,'' he said in the committee's opening debate on impeachment. `` Let me hasten to assert that that argument demeans my role here. It would make a mockery of our entire inquiry.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> resigned the presidency after the committee voted three articles of impeachment. Born in <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago-Kent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> and practiced law in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area until 1950 when he was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>. He served in the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from 1952 to 1962. While in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> was a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> manager of the Equal Rights Amendment and a sponsor of legislation providing that federal holidays such as Labor Day and Memorial Day be celebrated on Monday. <PERSON> McClory </PERSON>'s congressional district in the northern and western suburbs of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> was eliminated by reapportionment in 1981. Rather than opposing incumbent Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, also a Republican, in the expanded 10th District, he chose not to seek re-election in 1982. `` He will be best remembered for his leadership during the Watergate hearings and his abiding commitment to the rule of law,'' <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said Monday. `` Along with tens of thousands of people from our area, I share ... a tremendous sense of loss in <PERSON> Bob </PERSON>'s passing.'' <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> had lived in the nation's capital since leaving office and was a member of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON>. He is survived by his wife, two sons and a daughter. <PERSON> McClory </PERSON> will be buried Friday following a private service in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, his wife said. She said a public memorial service was scheduled for 11 a.m. Saturday at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bluff </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, where he had maintained a home since the 1930s.
