<HEAD>Delegate Says Burmese Leader's Resignation Accepted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s ruling political party on Monday accepted the resignation of strongman Ne Win after 26 years as head of the party, but opposed his call for a referendum on ending one-party rule, a delegate said. At the final session of a three-day congress, the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> also considered sweeping economic reforms designed to cure the country's deepening economic woes. The 77-year-old Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military coup, announced abruptly Saturday he was resigning. He cited bloody anti-government rioting in March and June and his age as key factors in his decision. Ne Win has been blamed for leading <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> into economic disaster during 26 years of isolationist policies. Five veteran party leaders also submitted their resignations Saturday. The party delegate, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the 1,061 delegates at the congress voted to accept <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>'s resignation and that of party vice chairman <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, also the country's president, but to retain them as `` inactive members. Official Radio <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> did not announce the decision, broadcasting only remarks by party General Secretary <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON> saying some delegates to the congress had favored approving the resignations. Political analysts speculated the official silence indicated division within party ranks on the course of the country. Ko also said the delegates rejected the resignations submitted by four of the party leaders because they were `` still young and energetic.'' The four included <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON>, party joint general secretary <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> and central executive committee members <PERSON> Tun </PERSON> <PERS