anti-government opposition but moved against leaders within his own ranks when they exhibited what he saw as too much independence. He also is blamed for turning resource-rich <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> into one of the nation's 10 poorest countries with an annual per capita income of less than $ 200. In a speech Sunday, <PERSON> Aye </PERSON> <PERSON> Ko </PERSON> admitted economic production had declined, working skills had deteriorated and `` losses and waste can not be controlled effectively.'' `` Because of these weaknesses and as a result of adverse repercussions from the world economic conditions today, the state economic situation is declining,'' he said. He called for an end to state control of many sectors and for allowing joint ventures between <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> entrepreneurs and foreign investors. Ne Win banned such ventures shortly after seizing power.
