<HEAD>Defendant Says Case Goes `All The Way To The Top'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man charged with illegally aiding the Nicaraguan Contra rebels pleaded innocent Monday and said his operations were approved `` all the way to the top'' of the White House. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>, 47, is one of seven men indicted on charges of violating the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Neutrality Act by secretly aiding the Contras in 1984 and 1985. `` This is a case of right and wrong,'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said after appearing before a federal magistrate. `` The soldiers are going to be hung and the generals will walk.'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON>, questioned why former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and other <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration figures connected to the Iran-Contra arms deal were not charged in the case, which covers a period when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had banned military aid to the Contras. Knowledge and approval of the aid operation `` went all the way to the top'' of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>. Asked if he meant the president, <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> repeated his statement. The former mercenary, who used the code name `` Colonel <PERSON> Flaco </PERSON>,'' said he received about $ 100,000 for the operations and added: `` it did not come from private sources.'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>'s defense also showed a document declassified during the congressional investigation into the Iran-Contra affair, saying it supports their contention that <PERSON> North </PERSON> was aware of the secret activities. The Jan. 27, 1985, memo to North, which is unsigned but which the defense says came from <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s aide <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Owen </PERSON>, specifically mentions <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>'s co-defendant <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Posey </PERSON>, head of Civilian Materiel Assistance of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. The memo says `` <PERSON> Posey </PERSON> is sending 4 people to -LRB- censored -RRB- to help with the training,'' and asks <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s approval of their departure date. It adds that <PERSON> Flaco </PERSON> `` is going to be working with the Indians,'' an apparent reference to the anti-Sandinista Miskito Indians on <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s eastern coast. <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said it was that operation that led to his disenchantment with the government's anti-Contra policies. `` They were not interested in getting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> back,'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said. `` They were interested in creating a situation in which the American military would have to come in.'' He said <PERSON> North </PERSON> had him thrown out of his base in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> `` with <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> submachine guns pointed at our heads'' because his operations were `` getting off the railroad track.'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> later began speaking out against <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policy on <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, and in subsequent memos <PERSON> North </PERSON> wrote that he had to be stopped. A Terrell co-defendant, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, was sentenced Friday to one day of probation and fined $ 50 by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Roettger </PERSON>, who could have sentenced him to 33 years in prison. <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> faces the same possible penalty as <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, but said he would not plead guilty despite <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' lenient treatment. `` I wo n't take a felony,'' said <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON> said the defense would subpoena witnesses and documents from government agencies, including the <ORGANIZATI