<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Collision     07-25 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Collision,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Captains of Sub, Fishing Boat Share Blame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The captains of a Japanese submarine and a pleasure fishing boat probably share blame for a weekend collision that killed nine people and left 21 missing, a <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official said Monday. A senior defense official said the submarine's crewmen should have done more to save the people in the fishing boat and were slow to notify rescue officials. The 2,200-ton sub Nadashio and the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru collided head-on Saturday southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> while the submarine was running on the surface. Some of the 48 people on the boat were thrown into the water and the boat sank in two minutes. Those missing are presumed dead. No injuries were reported among the sub's 75 crewmen. `` The investigation is n't complete yet, but it looks like both vessels were partly responsible for the accident,'' the <ORGANIZATION> MSA </ORGANIZATION> official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. Divers recovered the bodies of three more victims Monday in the waters near <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION>, about 30 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Rescue officials said 200 divers were searching for the 21 people still missing and others were on the ocean floor, attaching cables to the hull of the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru so it could be raised. <PERSON> Seiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishihiro </PERSON>, vice minister of state for defense, said the sub's crew was slow to tell rescue officials of the accident because its communications equipment only allowed it to talk to naval headquarters, not to the safety agency. Men on the sub should have `` grabbed three or four life preservers, if they were available, and jumped into the water'' to save people from the fishing boat, <PERSON> Nishihiro </PERSON> told reporters. Twenty-one minutes elapsed before the safety agency was told of the collision, according to news reports. Sixteen of the 19 people rescued were picked up by passing vessels and only three by the submarine, the reports said. One of those rescued died later. The Nadashio was crossing a busy shipping lane to enter <LOCATION> Yokosuka </LOCATION> naval base and was trying to avoid hitting a yacht when it collided with the boat, which a company fishing club had chartered for the weekend, Adm. <PERSON> Shuichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Higashiyama </PERSON> said Sunday. He said the fishing boat had not made an unexpected turn. Japanese maritime rules require the ship approaching from the left to take evasive action when two vessels appear to be on a collision course, with the other maintaining its course unless an accident is imminent. In Saturday's accident, the sub was approaching from the left and took such action, but the fishing boat also turned and a collision resulted. `` If the No. 1 <PERSON> Fujimaru </PERSON> had not turned to the left, there would not have been a collision,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official quoted <PERSON> Higashiyama </PERSON> as saying. `` I believe the submarine commander took the most appropriate measures to avoid an accident.''
