<FIRST>u a AM-CancerCauses Bjt   07-25 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Causes, Bjt,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Identify Genetic Defects That Lead To Colon Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers have identified genetic mutations that lead to the development of colon cancer, a critical step toward the development of better treatments for a form of cancer that kills 53,500 Americans annually. `` You can look at these genetic alterations as the causes of cancer _ just as you can look at bacteria as the causes of infection,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. `` Except it's more complicated in cancer.'' Just as the polio virus had to be discovered before the polio vaccine could be developed, so these genetic changes must be found before cancer can be prevented, <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> said Monday in a telephone interview. Research so far suggests that perhaps as many as seven genetic mutations must occur for olon cancer tumors to appear, <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> said. Five of those changes have now been identified, said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Speaking Monday at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> here, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said that colon cancer appears to be caused both by the activation of known cancer genes and by the failure of certain anti-cancer genes. `` The steps in the pathway are starting to be filled in,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. Understanding how these genetic changes produce colon tumors may allow doctors to distinguish between more severe and less severe forms of colon cancer in individuals, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said, and could one day lead to better cancer drugs. White has been one of the leaders in the study of the anti-cancer genes that protect against cancer _ the so-called recessive oncogenes. One such gene, identified in a rare form of eye cancer, has now been linked to breast cancer and to a common form of lung cancer, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. Another such gene was found by White in families with a rare kind of inherited colon cancer. Now, he said, failures of that anti-colon cancer gene have been found to occur in about half of the much more common form of colon cancer that is not inherited. Similarly, <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> said he has found two specific genetic variations in at least 75 percent of people with colon cancer. He has also found that a long-known cancer gene called the K-ras gene is altered in about half of the colon cancer cases he has studied. `` That kind of mutation is probably very important for the development of colon cancer,'' <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> said. `` And it suggests some relationship between environmental influences and cancer.'' Cancer is known to be caused, in part, by exposure to carcinogens in the environment, he explained. Such carcinogens could be triggering some of the genetic mutations that he and <PERSON> White </PERSON> are finding, he said. <PERSON> White </PERSON> said that some of these changes may produce polyps in the colon. These polyps, of the type that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has had removed, are thought to represent tissue in which some _ but not all _ of the colon cancer genetic mutations are present. <PERSON> Vogelstein </PERSON> said statistical studies of colon cancer suggest that perhaps no more than seven genetic mutations are required to produce colon cancer tumors. With five of those changes now identified, researchers may be close to identifying all of the principal genetic causes of colon cancer, he said, opening the way to research on new and better treatments for this disease.
</TEXT>
