<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill Golden Temple Head Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh extremists Monday opened fire at three leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, killing the head priest and a second official, and seriously injuring a third, police said. Police identified the dead as head priest <PERSON> Sohan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Shiromani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gurdwara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prabandhak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which manages <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine in the city of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, police said. The head of the committee, <PERSON> Mal </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghuman </PERSON>, suffered four bullet wounds and was hospitalized in critical condition, police said. According to police, the Sikh extremists armed with a AK-47 Chinese rifle sprayed gunfire at the three men at noon on a street in <LOCATION> Ludhiana </LOCATION>, about 55 miles west of the state capital of <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. Police said the gunmen fled on a motorcycle. The three were shot as they emerged from a board meeting of an engineering college, Indian news agencies said. There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack. A statewide manhunt was launched for the killers, said a <LOCATION> Ludhiana </LOCATION> police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The temple committee appointed the 60-year-old <PERSON> Sohan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> head priest in May after police and troops forced more than 150 Sikh extremists out of the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, which the militants used as a base to wage their guerrilla war for an independent homeland in the northwestern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. At least 42 people, most of them Sikh radicals, were killed during the siege. The head priest's predecessor and four other <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> high priests, who were jailed during the operation, remain in custody. The appointment of <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a moderate, was opposed by the militants, who also objected to the priest's efforts to exonerate <PERSON> Surjit </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnala </PERSON>, former chief minister of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barnala </PERSON> had been excommunicated from the Sikh faith by radical priests in charge of the temple after he defied their order to merge his moderate political party with the militants. Police reported four other deaths in extremist violence in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The latest victims raised to 1,560 the number of people killed by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> militants in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> this year. An estimated 690 of those killed have been Sikhs. The Sikh religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population, but they are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The Sikh militants claim they are being discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus.
