<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSDrugs     07-25 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Drugs,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Ruling On Import Of AIDS Treatment Drugs Gives Hope To Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN VEGA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government's decision to allow those who suffer from AIDS to import unproved drugs is a response to the gay community's frustrations about the search for a cure to the deadly disease, according to advocates for AIDS victims. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gostin </PERSON>, an attorney with the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, called the new program `` a signal advance in recognizing the gay and IV-drug constituencies that have been calling for this'' and grants AIDS patients `` a little bit of hope and reprieve.'' The government last week officially began allowing AIDS patients to import drugs not approved for sale in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as long as the drugs are for personal use. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> revealed the change Saturday to a hostile crowd at the Second International Lesbian and Gay Health Conference and AIDS Forum in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. He said the policy would also apply to drugs for other diseases. `` It's almost a shock because it's so contrary to the character and the tradition of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>,'' said `` It allows AIDS patients to make some choices about their own treatment,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratner </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lesbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which is sponsoring the conference on gay health issues. `` If you're dying, you do n't have a lot of choices,'' <PERSON> Ratner </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> had been repeatedly criticized by advocates of AIDS patients who say the government is not moving quickly enough to develop and test new drugs to treat the fatal, incurable disease. Increasingly desperate patients have been eager to try experimental treatment, and <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> was changing its policy even though scientists believe many of the drugs have not been proved safe and effective. `` From the AIDS person's point of view, they have nothing to lose and what they need is just some little optimism in their life. If there's a risk, I think that they should be able to make the decision about whether to assume that risk,'' <PERSON> Gostin </PERSON> said Sunday. <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, associate dean for education at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said the change responds to gay community's frustration `` that answers are n't coming more quickly.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> cautioned that although activists focus on the bureaucracy as if the bureaucracy was the problem, `` The real problem is that nature is very slow and reluctant to yield up her secrets.'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> had previously allowed unapproved drugs to be imported on an informal basis. One such drug was dextran sulfate, which the federal government is only now beginning to test in human trials as a treatment for AIDS. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s new policy will insure that people in need can import a small supply, generally enough for three months of treatment. The drugs must be only for personal use and not for sale. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. Homosexual or bisexual males account for 62 percent of the 68,220 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> AIDS cases counted by the government since June 1981. There have been 38,541 deaths, or 56 percent of the total cases, the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported last week.
