he said. `` The answer to release of the hostages is to release them. ... It's not a complex matter. ... They took them off the streets. They can put them back on the streets.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has persistently denied that his approval of the clandestine sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in 1985 and 1986 amounted to an arms-for-hostages deal. But a presidential commission headed by former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, concluded there was such a linkage, and so did <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Two hostages, the Rev. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, were released during the time of the transfers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which led to the subsequent diversion of sales proceeds to Nicaraguan rebels and _ eventually _ the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's worst scandal
