<HEAD>Trains Crash; Eight Slightly Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIGLE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An express train from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> crashed head-on into a standing freight train Monday and eight people were injured, although none seriously, authorities said. The Milan-Geneva express was traveling at more than 63 mph when it rammed the other train in the station of this southwestern Swiss town at 6:30 p.m., railway official <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Dessous-L'Eglise </PERSON> said at regional railway headquarters in <LOCATION> Lausanne </LOCATION>. All passengers were quickly evacuated from the coaches, a <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> television report from the scene said. Local police said eight passengers were injured, none of them seriously. Most damage was to the two locomotives, but both engineers escaped unhurt, Dessous-L'Eglise said. Officials suspected the accident was caused by a switching error. The railways launched an investigation.
