<HEAD>Legislator: Officials Preventing Ethiopian Jews From Emigrating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has denied visas to 150 Jews stranded in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, claiming they are not Jewish by Orthodox law, a legislator said Monday. <PERSON> Mattityahu </PERSON> <PERSON> Peled </PERSON>, a retired general in the Israeli army and a member of the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION>, said the Ethiopians have relatives in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and have waited several months in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s capital, for visas to the Jewish state. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jewish leaders apparently assured the Ethiopians the visas would be issued. The Ethiopians then abandoned their homes and most of their belongings to assemble in <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. But ultra-Orthodox Jewish officials at <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> decided against issuing the visas, saying the Ethiopians are not Jewish, <PERSON> Peled </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` People are suffering because their families are divided,'' <PERSON> Peled </PERSON> said. `` Those who are mixed up in this have no way back. We ca n't just leave them hanging in the air.'' About 7,500 Ethiopian Jews were flown to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> four years ago in a secret rescue operation code-named `` Operation Moses,'' and about 10,000 Jews remain in that African country, according to official estimates. Immigration and Absorption Minister <PERSON> Yaacov </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsur </PERSON> denounced <PERSON> Peled </PERSON>'s remarks Monday as a `` blood libel.'' Israeli officials consistently refuse to discuss emigration from <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, fearing publicity could harm the effort. <PERSON> Peled </PERSON> said his information came from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> office of the U.S.-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, an organization that has been active in trying to help Ethiopian Jews emigrate. Part of the information he received was published here by the respected daily <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayman </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, quoted <ORGANIZATION> AJC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifton </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as saying the organization's head office was unaware of the matter raised by <PERSON> Peled </PERSON>. But an official source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed <PERSON> Peled </PERSON>'s story. <PERSON> Tsur </PERSON> sent <PERSON> Clayman </PERSON> a telegram protesting the report, saying it `` shamed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s name,'' ministry spokesman <PERSON> Gad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Ari </PERSON> said. `` I checked this matter with all the authorities involved and I was assured unequivocally that there is no truth to this report,'' the telegram said. Many of the estimated 16,000 Ethiopian Jews in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> have faced discrimination from Israeli rabbis who often do not recognize them as Jewish, claiming they can not document their descendancy from the ancient faith. The Ethiopians claim they are descendants of the biblical King <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> and the Queen of Sheba who lived in the 10th century B.C. <PERSON> Peled </PERSON> said many of the Jews left in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> could be brought to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> if not for <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials, who belong to the ultra-Orthodox party Shas and have sole jurisdiction over visas. <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> is allied with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> enemies and thus reluctant to permit Jews to come here.
