<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Monsoon rains and lighting killed 116 people in the past two weeks, including 33 members of one family, and destroyed thousands of homes, a government official said Monday. More than a foot of rain caused flooding that inundated 7,000 homes in the eastern province of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Arshad </PERSON>, flood relief commissioner. He said 1,000 villages along the <LOCATION> Jhelum </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chinab </LOCATION> rivers in northern <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> province were flooded and more than 100,000 acres of land are under water, with cotton and rice crops the hardest hit. Lightning started a fire that killed 36 people, 33 of them from the same family, and consumed eight homes in northeastern <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, according to Pakistani television. The storms also were blamed for one of the worst bus accidents in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> this year. A bus was swept into a shallow ravine Thursday about 21 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, killing 70 people, police said. Witnesses said panicked passengers jumped into the water and drowned.
