<HEAD>Police Chiefs Say Study Needed on Effectiveness of Anti-Drug
Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of big-city police chiefs and criminologists said Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> are throwing money at anti-drug programs whose effectiveness never has been tested. The coalition, in a letter sent to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, urged that money be earmarked for research and development in the war on drugs to find out which programs are most effective. `` We are calling on the federal government to do what it is not doing now ... to include money for research ... and bring reflection and thought to our policy on drugs,'' <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouza </PERSON>, chief of police in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, said at a news conference where the letter was released. The coalition said 5 percent of total federal anti-drug funds should be set aside for research and development. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is expected to approve at least $ 1 billion for the war against drugs in the next fiscal year. Research could help determine how best to reduce demand for drugs, which treatment programs are most effective in keeping drug addicts from committing crimes and determine the costs and benefits of massive police crackdowns on drug-dealing locations, the police chiefs said in their letter. `` Throwing more money into existing programs will not answer these and other critical questions,'' the group said. `` We urge you to invest in better strategic knowledge for winning this war.'' The current war on drugs `` is characterized by defeat,'' <PERSON> Bouza </PERSON> said because of the lack of a coherent policy. Police need to know whether massive roundups of suspected drug dealers and raids on suspected drug operations are effective in deterring drug dealing, he said. The letter was signed by 46 police chiefs, sheriffs, law enforcement representatives and criminologists.
