<HEAD>Claiming Bodies Tougher Following Fake Death Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs penultimate graf to CORRECT that probation officer
ordered copy of autopsy report, sted ordered autopsy</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who want to claim a body from the coroner's office will first have to identify the corpse in a photo lineup under guidelines established after a woman gained custody of a body to fake her own death certificate. The <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> coroner now also requires people wishing to claim a body to show a driver's license and have fingerprints taken. Officials said that while they are sympathetic to grieving families, the new rules are necessary to prevent a similar scam in the future. The stricter standards came about after a woman trying to avoid creditors and probation officers gained custody of an unidentified body and tried to have her name registered as the deceased. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and her mother, <PERSON> Helene </PERSON> <PERSON> Tilch </PERSON>, were sentenced July 14 after pleading guilty to one count each of false personation, or creating a non-existent person. Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, 35, received a two-year sentence, and Ms. <PERSON> Tilch </PERSON>, who is 58 and in a wheelchair, got 16 months. Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> used the name <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Agee </PERSON>, called the coroner's office in December and said she was looking for her dead sister. The investigator asked for a description of the dead woman and Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> essentially described herself. Her height, hair color and general description _ a heavyset white woman in her mid-30s _ matched that of an unidentified body unclaimed since its discovery Oct. 25 alongside a highway. The woman apparently died of a drug overdose. Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and her mother were very emotional when shown the body. `` They were good at their craft,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Spada </PERSON>, a supervising coroner's investigator. `` And their craft was scamming people.'' The coroner's office, which handles 17,000 to 20,000 bodies a year, released the body to the two women, who had it cremated and mailed the death certificate to Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s probation officers, prosecutors said. <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> probation officer <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Raquel </PERSON> ordered a copy of the autopsy report, and the results showed the dead woman had undergone a hysterectomy and was covered with tattoos. <PERSON> Raquel </PERSON> knew the two characteristics did not fit Ms. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and called police. The dead woman's ashes have been returned to the coroner's office, where they will remain should the woman's real relatives come forward
