<HEAD>Cincinnati Archbishop OK After Brain Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> Archbishop <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON> underwent a four-hour brain operation Monday to seal off a ruptured blood vessel that could have killed him if it had not been treated, his chief surgeon said. Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a pioneer in laser surgery who conducted the operation, said <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON> could leave the hospital after a week and return to work in four to six weeks. <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON>, 53, was listed in good condition. <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON>, Roman Catholic archbishop since 1982 in the 550,000-member Archdiocese of <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, suffered the aneurysm near the base of his brain Saturday while vacationing in <LOCATION> Gatlinburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>. He was transported to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION> for initial treatment, then was moved by helicopter Sunday to <ORGANIZATION> Good </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Samaritan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, a Catholic hospital. <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON> survived because his hemorrhaging stopped after the rupture and because of good treatment he received at the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> hospital, <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> told a news conference Monday. `` I really felt today like I was being guided. I never saw an operation go so smoothly,'' said <PERSON> Tew </PERSON>, chairman of neurosurgery at Good Samaritan. <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> said the medical team cut into <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON>'s skull and used two 5-millimeter stainless steel clips to seal off the aneurysm, a sac formed when a weakened blood vessel wall bulges. That should prevent another rupture, <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> said. Doctors have bypassed the artery and rerouted the brain's blood supply to another artery. <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON> has an excellent prognosis and shows no signs of paralysis or other damage, <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> said. `` There is no damage to the brain itself,'' <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> said. `` He does n't seem to have any trouble at all right now.'' <PERSON> Tew </PERSON> said the aneurysm is the result of a congenital weakness in the wall of the artery, which gets thinner over time. About 40,000 Americans suffer blood vessel ruptures each year and approximately 15,000 of them die as a result. Auxiliary Bishop <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> is running the archdiocese in <PERSON> Pilarczyk </PERSON>'s absence.
