<HEAD>Instructor Pleads Innocent to Involuntary Manslaughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `If the..', to restore dropped first name of
victim Mirecki.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The only one of five enlisted <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> instructors charged with involuntary manslaughter in the training death of a 19-year-old recruit pleaded innocent Monday. A military judge also set an Aug. 29 trial date in the court-martial of Petty Officer 2nd Class <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Combe </PERSON>, but said he may delay it if a defense lawyer could not appear because of his wife's illness. If the date stands, <ORGANIZATION> Combe </ORGANIZATION>'s trial would start a week after that of Lt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Torchia </PERSON>, officer in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swimmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, died March 2. Four other enlisted instructors were charged only with conspiracy to commit battery and received nonjudicial punishments including reductions in rank and loss of pay. <PERSON> Torchia </PERSON> also was offered nonjudicial punishment but chose a court-martial in an effort to clear himself. <PERSON> Combe </PERSON>, however, received no choice. His court-martial was ordered by Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman, chief of naval education an training, following an investigative hearing last month. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has accused <PERSON> Combe </PERSON> of holding <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s head under water after he was pushed into the pool. Besides manslaughter, <PERSON> Combe </PERSON> is charged with battery and conspiracy to commit battery. Instructors allegedly forced <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> into a pool after he had panicked, climbed out, held on to an equipment rack and shouted that he was quitting the course. At the investigative hearing, a pathologist testified that <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> had a phobia about being dragged under water, which triggered heart failure followed by drowning. <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> was taking part in a practice rescue in which the instructors, playing the role of panicked air crash victims, grasped recruits in a head-hold. Witnesses at the hearing gave conflicting testimony on whether <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Combe </LOCATION>'s grasp or had extricated himself from the instructor's head-hold when he collapsed. The military judge, Cmdr. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Radlinski </PERSON>, denied a request by defense lawyers to delay the trial until late September. Prosecutor Lt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> had argued for starting the trial as early as Monday.
