<FIRST>r i AM-JournalDebunks     07-25 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Journal Debunks,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Words Over Experiment with Inexplicable Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bitter words circulated in the scientific community Monday over reports that this week's edition of a respected science journal will debunk an experiment that defies scientific theory. The experiment baffled researchers because it appeared to use sound methods to prove the impossible: that natural proteins called antibodies that react with certain blood cells will continue to react when diluted far beyond the point where they should theoretically be able to do so. Nature, a science weekly, published the antibody findings in its June 30 edition, but in an unusual `` editorial reservation'' declared: `` There is no physical basis for such an activity.'' It said experts it later chose to review the research did not believe the result, but could not fault the conduct of the experiments, and the journal promised to have independent investigators observe repetitions of the experiments. The report of the investigation is to appear in this week's edition of Nature and advance word, leaked to the French press, is that it dismisses the experiment as fanciful, poorly conducted and of no scientific value Editors of Nature have refused comment, but sources at the magazine confirmed privately that an article will appear that discredits the experiment. They also confirmed reports that Nature's independent investigators were <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Randi </PERSON>, a professional magician from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> known for studying unusual scientific claims, and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, an investigator of scientific fraud. `` Nature is going to produce a totally and completely negative report on the experiment,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Benveniste </PERSON> of the French medical institute <ORGANIZATION> INSERM </ORGANIZATION>, who produced the inexplicable results at his <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> laboratory. Researchers in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> say they have duplicated <PERSON> Benveniste </PERSON>'s results. <PERSON> Benveniste </PERSON> and the sources at Nature magazine both said the report does not suggest cheating was involved. <PERSON> Benveniste </PERSON> said in a telephone interview he had seen Nature's article and `` I do n't consider it as serious I think it will harm Nature.'' <PERSON> Randi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> `` made an enormous amount of mistakes that I will outline in my answer to Nature,'' <PERSON> Benveniste </PERSON> said, adding that the controls the investigators used were inadequate. Controls are special samples used in laboratories to check testing procedures. Quoting from the rebuttal he is sending to Nature, <PERSON> Beneviste </PERSON> said: `` All in all, the judgment is based on one dilution series, tested on two bloods, in awful technical and psychological conditions. Outrageous.'' He would not specify what Nature's article says because the magazine has not yet released it publicly, but quoted a passage he said would `` make their whole report auto-destruct.'' As quoted by <PERSON> Beneviste </PERSON>, the passage says: `` Thus we believe that many of the experiments whose results are regarded as significant are artifacts of statistical noise. But plainly this does n't apply to all the data _ for example the fourth experiment in the series.'' That means the investigators had failed to discredit all the experiments, he said. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortner </PERSON>, an immunology research associate at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION>, which reported duplicating the experiment, said last month: `` It's unbelievable and it breaks all rules.'' She said in an interview at the time that the supposedly impossible reaction occurs even at extreme levels of dilution when theoretically no antibody molecules are left in the solution. `` This has really shaken up our world,'' she said. `` Even people who have seen this phenomenon find it hard to believe.''
</TEXT>
