<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Attack Bowling Alley In San Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Guerrillas attacked and set fire to a bowling alley in the capital Monday in response to the police disruption of an anti-government march, the establishment's manager said No one was reported hurt. No group made independent claims of responsibility for the attack. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Bolerama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jardin </ORGANIZATION>, said 10 to 12 masked men with pistols and at least one submachine gun burst into the bowling alley and identified themselves as `` urban commandos'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The front, a coalition of five guerrilla groups, has waged an 8-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government, but the fighting in recent years has been largely restricted to the countryside. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said the guerrillas made the about 30 patrons `` lie face down on the floor and took from them money they said was a ` contribution' to the cause. They said the attack was in reprisal for the government's repression of Thursday's march.'' The guerrillas then doused several pool tables in a room adjoining the main bowling area with gasoline and set them afire, and the flames spread, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said. Firefighters arrived within 15 minutes and extinguished the blaze. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> estimated damage at $ 20,000. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said none of the bowling alley owners has any connection with the government, and that he did not understand why the establishment was selected as a target. Last Thursday, police used tear gas and fired shots in the air to break up an anti-government demonstration in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Protesters then burned at least nine vehicles. Human rights groups estimate more than 65,000 people have been killed in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> since the civil war began in October 1979.
