<SECOND>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Pakistan, U.S. `Fan Flames Of War'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> lodged a strongly worded protest with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Monday, accusing <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of violating peace accords and pleading with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general to end this `` license to kill.'' <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> charged the two nations with fanning `` the flames of war'' and engaging in `` blind terrorism.'' A U.N.-sponsored political agreement was signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, providing for Soviet troop withdrawal over nine months, non-interference in <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> affairs and return of Afghan refugees who have fled the civil war. The accords were signed by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which acted as spokesman for the anti-Marxist Afghan guerrillas, and were guaranteed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The guerrillas did not sign the accords. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> cited in his letter to Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> `` the new wave of ferocious and adventurist actions by extremists linked with the Peshawar-based alliance of seven -LRB- guerrilla groups -RRB- who have created appalling tragedies with missile barrages on <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and other cities.'' Major Afghan anti-government guerrillas are based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> is the Afghan capital. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> urged the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief to end the purported violations of the Afghan accords by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has been aiding the guerrillas. `` The people of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> expect that the means of interference and the shipment of weapons will stop and the license to kill shall no more be issued,'' said the letter, the latest in a series of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> protests by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` Is it not high time for <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, principal signatory of the accords, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the state guarantor, which still fan the flames of war, to understand the futility of blind terrorism?'' <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>'s letter said. His letter complained that on July 15, 17, 19 and 20, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> residents were killed in bomb blasts by guerrillas based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. In the past 1 -LCB- months, it said, 177 missiles were fired into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, killing 75 people and injuring 98. The letter said the guerrillas want to disrupt the government policy of reconciliation, create panic among the civilian population, frighten refugees from returning to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and jeopardize the future of peace. It said <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is carrying out the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords and Soviet troops are withdrawing on schedule, `` but brazen violations are being carried out by the other side.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been supplying the guerrillas with an estimated $ 500 million annually in arms and military supplies channeled through <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. It vowed to continue the supplies as long as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> keeps up its military support of the Afghan government. The Afghan accords prohibit <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s interference in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s affairs. But weapons supply from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is not banned. A separate agreement signed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> allows them to continue supplying their respective sides. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> at the end of 1979 to prop up the pro-Soviet government and stayed on to help fight the guerrillas. The estimated 115,000 Soviet troops began withdrawing May 15 and are to complete the pullout by Feb. 15.
