<FIRST>r a AM-DecodingDisease     07-25 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Decoding Disease,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher: Tiny Genetic Defect Could Explain Origin Of Many
Diseases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Microscopic defects in the body's energy-generating system have been shown to cause blindness and might also cause major diseases of the heart, brain, liver and kidneys, a researcher said Monday <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said his research is the first to link a specific disease to defects in tiny chemical factories called mitochondria, which convert food into energy to support living cells. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> has for years been pursuing the notion that defects in mitochondrial genes could be important in many human diseases, and now he says he has proved his case. In a research paper that has been submitted to a journal for publication, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said he demonstrates a link between a precise, pinpoint mitochondrial defect and a rare inherited disease known as LHON, which can lead to blindness. `` I feel now statistically this is the right answer,'' <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said at the <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, where he is helping to teach a course in genetics. Dr. <PERSON> Berkeley </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, who is familiar with <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>'s research, said, `` I think it is an important step, but people have been suspecting this for a long time _ so I do n't think it's `` The work is certainly very good and demonstrates it -LRB- the link -RRB- very nicely,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. The disease called <PERSON> Leber </PERSON>'s hereditary optic neuropathy, or <ORGANIZATION> LHON </ORGANIZATION>, is very rare, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said. But he has also linked mitochondrial defects to several other rare genetic diseases, and he is convinced that these defects will be shown to be the cause of some major degenerative diseases for which the cause has not yet been found. Mitochondria are tiny structures inside cells that convert carbohydrates into energy-carrying molecules that can be dispatched around the cell to keep its machinery running _ and keep it alive. Each mitochondrion has a tiny set of 13 known genes that are entirely separate from the genes and chromosomes that carry most hereditary information, and that are responsible for most hereditary diseases. The mitochondrial genes are passed on to offspring only by mothers, through their eggs. Sperm carry only a few mitochondria, and those mitochondria are not incorporated into the developing offspring. Furthermore, they reproduce and mutate rapidly, compared with other genes, and thus the diseases they cause can appear and disappear in individuals and in succeeding generations, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said. That's why it was so difficult to prove that they were causing disease. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said that cyanide is known to poison people by damaging their mitochondrial genes. Cyanide causes disorders of the brain, heart, liver, kidneys and muscle, he said. It may therefore be possible that genetic defects in the mitochondria can also cause such disorders, he said. In particular, he mentioned cardiomyopathy, a gradual weakening of the heart muscle for which there is no cure, except for a heart transplant. Its cause is unknown. Because mitochondria reproduce and mutate rapidly, it is possible that defects that appear during an individual's lifetime can trigger this harmful degeneration in the heart, he said. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> emphasized that with the exception of the few rare disorders to which he has linked the mitochondria, his ideas about the role of mitochondria in disease are speculation.
</TEXT>
