<HEAD>Senate Thwarts Two Helms Attempt To Restrict Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Monday thwarted two attempts by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> to eliminate or restrict the federal family planning program, denounced by the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> as evidence of the government `` going out of control.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 65-21 to kill a <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment that would have deleted the $ 140 million Title X family planning program from a spending bill for the departments of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, and Education. The chamber voted 54-34 to kill another <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment that would have barred all spending by <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> unless the secretary required by Jan. 31 that unmarried dependent minors 17 or under have written parental consent to get contraceptives or prescriptions for contraceptives from federally funded clinics. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also approved by voice vote a `` conscience clause'' saying none of the money in the bill can be used to require any person or entity to perform or facilitate abortions. The provision applies to medical personnel or denominational hospitals with religious or moral objections to abortion. The amendments arose during consideration of the $ 137 billion appropriations bill for the three departments. The money is for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. Title X provides money to states, local health departments and private groups for family planning clinics serving primarily low-income women. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> alleged that Planned Parenthood, a major recipient of Title X money, is using federal funds for abortion-related services and that in the last 10 years, Title X money has been used for `` secret sex programs for our nation's teen-agers.'' `` The federal government takes money from American parents and then uses that money to give contraceptives ... to their children,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` This is wrong. This is immoral. This is evidence of the federal government going out of control and moving far beyond what our founding fathers had in mind.'' `` Title X is not an abortion program. It's a knowledge program,,'' rejoined Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>. `` I wish it were that all teen-agers would go to their parents for advice in this area But the fact is they do n't ... There are those situations where there is no home. Then who does the job?'' Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., said lawmakers like himself who oppose abortion should not handicap family planning clinics in any way `` We'd be taking a step backwards, in the wrong direction,'' by requiring parental consent, he said. `` We would have more and more unwanted and unplanned babies ...'' <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor-HHS </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittee, urged senators to vote their convictions on the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendments and not cave in to political pressure `` We all know in our heart of hearts how we ought to stand on it,'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said of the parental consent amendment. `` It's a question of how we are recorded on it ... Are you going to trigger some group against you or not?'' The abortion amendment was sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, who said so-called conscience clauses currently are written into some laws but not others. `` Absent this amendment, persons involved with programs -LRB- in this bill -RRB- might or might not be protected in the exercise of their conscience in this matter,'' <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> said. `` In some cases they would ... In other cases they would not.''
