<HEAD>Saudi King Looks To `Amicable' Way Of Ending Rift With Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 King <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> said Monday that he regretted the absence of Iranians at the annual Moslem pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and expressed hope of an amicable settlement of the rift between his country and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Fahd, speaking to leaders of Moslem delegations in a speech broadcast on <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> radio, said: `` I regret not having seen the pilgrims of the Iranian nation participating with their Moslem brothers at these sacred spots.'' The Saudi king said Iranian pilgrims still were welcomed to `` the land of Islam'' and blamed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for decisions that led to their absence this year. `` What we hope is that these matters be settled in an amicable manner and that the Moslems be gathered together in one frame,'' he added. Saudi official figures released Monday said 1,379,556 Moslems _ including 762,755 from abroad and 616,801 from within the kingdom _ gathered this year for the pilgrimage, or hajj, which culminated Sunday with the start of the four-day Eid al-Adha or Feast of Sacrifice. About 145,000 pilgrims from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> went to Mecca for the 1987 hajj. Iranian pilgrims held demonstrations last year in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, despite a ban on political protests, and 402 people died, including 275 Iranians. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> said they died in a stampede, but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> accused Saudi police of shooting at the pilgrims. Citing terrorism and subversion, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> last April broke diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which has advocated taking away from the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> royal family custodianship of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, Islam's holiest sites. Saudi authorities earlier announced that the number of pilgrims would be restricted this year to one for every 1,000 residents of each Moslem country. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> boycotted the hajj to protest the cuts, and its government-controlled news media said demonstrations occurred again this year. The Saudis have denied those reports. Fahd made no reference to the Iranian reports of protests and referred only indirectly to the 1987 riots. What happened last year, he said, was `` over ... and thanks be to God, wisdom and logic prevailed and matters were put in their perspective,'' he said. All of the world's 850 million Moslems are expected to make at least one pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> if they can afford it. Mecca is the birthplace of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, the founder of Islam. Its Grand Mosque houses the <LOCATION> Kaaba </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holiest shrine. Pilgrims also made journeys this week to shrines in <LOCATION> Medina </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s base for his 7th Century conquest of Arabia and the spread of the religion.
