<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told Conservative Jews on Monday he feels control of the faith by Orthodox rabbis would harm Jewish unity. In an emotional speech frequently interrupted by applause, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rabbinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> that his <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has `` decided to keep Jewish life together as a matter of principle.'' `` We have decided profoundly, seriously and permanently not to discriminate Jewish people within the Jewish life and not to divide the Jewish people,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Rabbinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> represents 1,200 Conservative Jewish leaders worldwide. It began a six-day 88th annual convention Monday. Conservatives are struggling against what they contend is discrimination by Orthodox rabbis, who dominate <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s state religious offices. More than 100 rabbis demonstrated against alleged discrimination Sunday outside the seat of the Chief Rabbinate, which is <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s highest state religious body and is controlled by Orthodox Jews <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> pledged to defend Conservative Jews against Orthodox attempts to pass a `` Who's a Jew'' law that would change the status of the non-Orthodox. `` Who is a Jew?,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> asked. `` I can answer it very simply. There is no Jew who can exclude another Jew from the Jewish life.'' His statements deviated from past <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> policy of cultivating religious parties as political allies. Israeli analysts recently suggested <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> has abandoned hope of forming a coalition with religious parties after parliamentary elections in November. Labor faces a tough campaign against Pri