<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Debates over biblical accounts of the virgin birth of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> and his resurrection have done more damage to the spread of Christianity in the East than have non-Christians, a Pakistani bishop said Monday. `` The theological controversies in the West can strike a fatal blow to the spread of the Gospel,'' <PERSON> Bashir </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwan </PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION> Hyderabad </LOCATION>, said. He addressed other Anglican bishops on the ninth day of the three-week <ORGANIZATION> Lambeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. Among those in the audience was <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s Bishop of Durham <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. In 1984, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> aroused controversy by suggesting the virgin birth, the resurrection and other miracles reported in the New Testament were symbolic stories and did not actually happen. The Lambeth Conference of 525 bishops representing the world's 70 million Anglicans, including members of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Episcopalians, meets every 10 years <PERSON> Jiwan </PERSON> said `` disbelief in the bodily resurrection of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> and the claim that it was only a spiritual experience of resurrection in the minds of the disciples raises the question of the authority of the Bible. `` The Bible is the divine source of revelation and the touchstone of Christian doctrine.'' He added it appeared Moslems believe more of Christianity than <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> theologians who have `` laid down'' their spiritual weapons. <PERSON> Jiwan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> were among three speakers discussing evangelization and culture, but their subjects were not linked. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said Christian churches destroyed the credibility of the Gospel by competing to recruit new members. Evangelization must be wide-ranging, not mutually exclusive, and confront social, political and economic issues, he said. Christians should consider how their social structures, political policies and `` economic exploitations'' diminished them in God's image, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. Bishop <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gitari </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, the first African bishop to address the full conference, criticized church laws for allowing tolerance and pastoral care to divorcees while disciplining polygamists. `` We see no contradiction in extending pastoral care to divorcees, despite <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>' strictures against divorce,'' he said. `` Yet we maintain a rigid disciplinary stance againmst polygamy despite <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>' silence on the subject.''
