<HEAD>New Regulations Adopted For Horse Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New regulations announced Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will allow horse shows for all breeds to continue, said a senator who had monitored the developments. `` The negotiations have been long and complex,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky. `` But I think everyone has emerged a winner. Horse shows for many breeds were closed earlier this year after the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit seeking enforcement of regulations, primarily for walking horses, that had adversely affected much of the industry. The regulations approved Monday permanently replace interim rules that had been imposed to allow the continuation of horse shows while the regulations were being negotiated. Major provisions of the new regulations include a new uniform standard for pads that would apply to all horse breeds; new rules on pad material; rejection of a proposal by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to further limit the weight of horseshoes; and new guidelines on examination procedures for horses exhibited in walking horse shows. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> had solicited comments in April on the interim regulations. During the last several months, <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> sponsored negotiations with major horse organizations addressed by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> interim rules. The negotiations resulted in a joint comment on behalf of over 100 national horses organizations being sent to Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>. In the letter, the organizations recommended the new regulations adopted Monday. `` These recommendations were reached after weeks of negotiations with every major horse organization throughout the country,'' <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> said in a statement released by his office. `` Now that the regulations are permanent, horse shows throughout <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and the nation can continue without the fear of being shut down.''
