<SECOND>AM-Korean War-35 Years Later, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>America Starts to Remember Forgotten War In Korea</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf bgng ``The war began ... '' to delete reference
to boundary remaining 38th Parallel at end of war; SUBS 11th graf
bgng ``More artillery ... '' to delete reference to amount of
artillery fired.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation is finally starting to consecrate a forgotten war which stirred neither patriotic fervor nor domestic protest, the brutal, anti-communist crusade in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> which killed 54,000 Americans and ended with an uneasy armistice 35 years ago Wednesday. World War II veterans returned home triumphantly to ticker-tape parades. Returning <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans often met hostility. Many of the 1.5 million men and women who served in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> during the 37 months of fighting simply came home. For years, images of their sacrifice have been summoned up only during broadcasts of MASH, the television comedy series. `` They went in quietly and went out quietly,'' says one of them, retired Army Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F.C </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` They were welcomed back home with an attitude of indifference. There were no parades, but there were no put-downs either.'' Today, only 40 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> public is old enough to recall the Korean War in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> today. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still maintains one full division on the demarcation line.'' But now, perhaps inspired by the belated recognition given <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans, the dead and living from <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> are being honored with resolutions from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and space on the capital's National Mall for a multimillion-dollar memorial. This week, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> vets are gathered in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a round of ceremonies which, though mostly low-key, amount to the most extensive array of commemorative events since the fighting stopped in 1953, according to <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON>. The war began after the Soviet-trained North Korean army crossed the 38th Parallel into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on June 25, 1950. It ended in stalemate on July 27, 1953. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON>, writing in a recent edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, points out that the war was not popular among Americans and was the first in which <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> essentially declared the enemy's homeland off-limits to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fighting forces. <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON> says that body counts became more important than real estate as <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> and Chinese units staged human-wave assaults that accounted for many of the 1.4 million dead or wounded communist troops. The war _ called a `` conflict'' and `` police action'' by the <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> administration _ saw the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> use of helicopters to evacuate wounded, according to <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON>. Fighting under a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> banner, 54,260 Americans died in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, 33,643 of them in battle. In the nine years of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, 58,149 Americans died, 47,396 in battle. On a day-to-day basis, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was far bloodier. The Pentagon says that 1,269 Americans are still listed as prisoners of war or missing in action from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. It has no specific numbers for GIs still missing from the Korean War, but it numbers the POWs at 389. It was n't until 1985 that <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> vets even had their own organization, founded by retired Army 1st Sgt. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> of Half Moon, N.Y. The <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has grown from 39 charter members to more than 3,000 and is a central participant in this week's 35th anniversary ceremonies. <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON> now is working out of a sparsely furnished office at the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> as executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which is spearheading the drive to build the memorial in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He said the push for the memorial began after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> veterans began the offensive that culminated in the dedicated of their monument on the Mall in 1982. `` The <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> vets were saying, ` where's ours?''' he said. After several years of groundwork, organizing and lobbying, the <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> vets won permission from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> this year to erect a privately financed memorial on the Mall. The initial budget is $ 6 million, with veterans required to repay any seed money advanced from the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>. The location is still undecided, but the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Battle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monuments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is recommending a site near the Lincoln Memorial and across a reflecting pool from the Vietnam Memorial. Once the location is chosen, the board will hold a competition to select a design to reflect the board's concept that it `` must radiate a message that is at once inspirational in content and timeless in meaning ... unique in concept, designed for public use.'' <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON> says that $ 2.2 million has been raised so far, with $ 1 million coming from <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of the Korean automaker, and nearly $ 300,000 coming from <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> dealers. Among some 3,500 contributors, the Disabled American Veterans have given $ 500,000, the VFW $ 250,000 and the Paralyzed Veterans of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> $ 100,000, according to <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON>, whose goal is `` to put up a good memorial on what I call everybody's front lawn.'' <PERSON> Kenney </PERSON> says that a Korean War memorial is needed because `` in the long run, the nation owes some form of recognition to those who, without all the fanfare of a war to save the world, marched off quietly to fight for freedom for a people they never heard of because their country asked them to do so.''
</TEXT>
