<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said Monday it will withdraw from Iranian territory captured in the past week, prompting hopes of quiet on the long border warfront when peace talks begin at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Announcers interrupted regular state television programs to say the army would withdraw on Tuesday from territory captured in the central border region. `` They will be withdrawn in line with our declared policy that we have no territorial ambitions in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' said a military communique read by the announcers. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Monday night he is optimistic a truce date in the Iran-Iraq war can be set within 10 days. The war began in September 1980. Appearing on the `` The MacNeil @ Lehrer Newshour'' TV program with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief were <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassadors <PERSON> Ismat </PERSON> <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ja'Afar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kittani </PERSON> announced that by midnight Monday <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> time, `` all Iraqi forces will have completed their withdrawal to our side of the internationally recognized border. ... We have no intention of occupying and holding Iranian territory for bargaining.'' He refused to deny a complaint by <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons in its latest military offensive. <PERSON> Mahallati </PERSON> also s