<HEAD>Puerto Ricans Mark Anniversaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VILLALBA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of people gathered on a mountaintop in central Puerto Rico Monday for a quiet ceremony marking the 10th anniversary of the police killing of two young supporters of independence for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. Two other commemorative dates fell on Monday _ the 36th anniversary of the signing of the constitution that established <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> as a semi-autonomous U.. <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION>, and the 90th anniversary of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military occupation of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> in 1898 Young girls laid flowers and <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> flags on the spot where <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Soto </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrivi </PERSON>, 18, and <PERSON> Arnaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Dario </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosado </PERSON>, 24, were shot on July 25, 1978, and speakers demanded that those responsible for the deaths be brought to justice. `` We're here to demand that the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government fulfill its promises to jail those officials of -LRB- former Gov. -RRB- <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcelo </PERSON>'s government who covered up these murders,'' said <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallisa </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcelo </PERSON> of the pro-statehood <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was governor at the time of the killings. The Popular Democrats are now in control. About 70 miles away, in the capital city of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, an estimated 50,000 people gathered in front of the seaside capitol building for speeches, singing and dancing to mark the constitution's 36th anniversary. A jubilant Gov. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, who is seeking re-election in November, spoke for 30 minutes about his administration's achievements. Then he rolled up his shirt-sleeves and leaped off the 12-foot-high stage into the waiting arms of supporters and circulated through the crowd pressed around him. Four <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> jets roared overhead in formation as dozens of people stood on a hill across from the capitol, holding up red, white and blue placards to form a Puerto Rican flag. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> ceded <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1898 after the Spanish American War. Puerto Ricans are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens with most of the rights of their mainland counterparts except that in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> they can not vote for president. Most islanders are divided between supporting the current commonwealth status or statehood. About 5 percent voted in the last election for the party that supports independence from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rosado </PERSON> and <PERSON> Soto </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrivi </PERSON> were killed in a police ambush when they went up to a remote mountain called <ORGANIZATION> Cerro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maravilla </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Marvel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, purportedly to gain publicity for independence by blowing up a transmitter. They were led there by a police informant, who has since been assassinated by an underground group that said it was avenging the two deaths. Police first said they killed the two in an exchange of gunfire, but a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> investigation later revealed that <PERSON> Rosado </PERSON> and <PERSON> Soto </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrivi </PERSON> were shot at close range while on their knees after having surrendered. Six policemen are serving long prison sentences for murder in the killings and eight officers in all have been convicted of perjury for lying to two federal grand juries. The killings are still under investigation. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and a specially appointed independent prosecutor are trying to find out if government officials were involved in the cover-up.
</TEXT>
