<HEAD>Salvadoran Army Leader Says Key to War is Winning over the Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MIGUEL, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>, a combat-tempered colonel who is a front-runner to be armed forces commander, says the military's chief aim in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s civil war should be winning the loyalty of the rural poor, not killing guerrillas. He said in an interview at his 3rd Brigade headquarters in this provincial capital 85 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> that soldiers should help improve living standards for the rural poor, campesinos as they are called. `` Build a coop and set up a chicken-raising enterprise, teach them how to plant vegetables, the raising of pigs,'' he said. `` These are cheap projects, more immediate. The people see problems resolved more quickly, and it leaves them with a tool they can use for life.'' <LOCATION> Ponce </LOCATION>, 41, the commander of the 3rd Brigade, added that he has set aside some of his troops for that purpose and indicated he believed similar efforts should be made all around the countryside by the military. High-ranking military sources say he is the most likely officer to succeed Gen. <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Blandon </PERSON> as chief of the joint chiefs of staff when <PERSON> Blandon </PERSON> retires in the coming months. <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> said he uses two kinds of military units in his command. `` One is eminently operative, for carrying out offensive military operations that principally strike -LRB- guerrilla -RRB- commanders at different levels. These are units trained for night operations, ambushes and long-range patrols. The other type of unit carries out first a military role but then fulfills a political function,'' he explained. `` We can not think that solely by military means we are going to resolve this war. Even if we kill all the subversives, the problem will not end. Such deplorable socio-economic conditions would remain that it -LRB- the insurgency -RRB- could easily revive. `` This is an ideological and psychological war, a war for the masses and a war of oganization.'' Of the political work, he added, `` you always have to give the campesinos something concrete, because they ca n't eat words.'' Referring to two previous, and unsuccessful, development projects designed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> advisers to win over the populace, he said: `` It's no longer a matter of building schools or paving roads. What we're doing requires less sophistication and less bureaucracy.'' <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> said his strategy is producing positive results in his eastern command zone. But two commanders of the guerrillas' <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, known as the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, contended in interviews broadcast by the rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos that an army that represents <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s status quo can never win the poor farmer's heart. Commander <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Melendez </PERSON> said the fact that rebel forces are still active in all of the country's 14 provinces, although outnumbered 8-1 by government troops, means the army `` has failed militarily.'' `` The root of this failure is in the nature of the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, which arises precisely from those same popular sectors,'' he said. Rebel commander <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON> said in a separate interview in June: `` The objectives in the mind of each combatant have to be expressions of the true interests of his people ... and that's why neither -LRB- Defense Minister Gen. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Vides </PERSON> <PERSON> Casanova </PERSON> nor the Americans could ever convert -LRB- the rural poor -RRB- to the cause of foreign interests that have nothing to do with our particular problems.'' The rural poor make up 60 percent of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s population of 5.1 million. Four <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> experts who studied <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> also see the key to the war as lying with the loyalty of the rural poor. Cols. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallums </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, A.J. <PERSON> Bacevich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> addressed the subject in a paper they wrote in March at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, titled `` American Military Policy in Small Wars: The Case of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>.'' Of the campaign for the allegiance of the populace, the officers concluded that `` disappointment with the outcome -LRB- of previous efforts -RRB- convinced hard-core Salvadoran commanders to forget about ` hearts and minds' in favor of pursuing guerrillas.'' Of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> role, the paper says: `` Despite their appreciation that winning popular support remains as the ultimate strategic aim in counterinsurgency, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials have yet to devise adequate mechanisms to achieve that aim.''
</TEXT>
