<HEAD>Venice Preparing to Test System to Protect It from Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the sirroco blows up the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> from the deserts of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s lagoon swells up and spills into the city. Sirens sound a mournful reminder: <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> is losing its struggle with the environment. Even at the height of summer, gondoliers ply their trade over murky green and often foul-smelling canals alive with algae thriving on tons of raw sewage. But a group of scientists and engineers are finally preparing to test the prototype of a system to protect <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> from the sea that once protected it. After nearly four years of work and $ 700 million in costs, the engineers in the fall will install at the <LOCATION> Lido </LOCATION> entrance to the <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> lagoon the prototype of a mobile dike designed to stem the flood tides that have troubled the city's past and threaten its future. `` The goal of the project is to save <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, to save the life of the lagoon, to save the port, to save the historic city and the economic life of its people,'' said <PERSON> Maurio </PERSON> <PERSON> Fabris </PERSON>, director of public relations for the Venezia Nuova -LRB- <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> -RRB- consortium. He said the consortium of 26 Italian companies is executing the 10-year, $ 4.4 billion-project to build a line of mobile dikes across the lagoon's three entrances, shore up the sea walls and islands, preserve the canals and restore the ecological balance in the polluted lagoon. Venetians built their island city along 150 winding canals to protect themselves from invaders. Now the threat comes from the sea that once guarded them. High tides flood the city about 100 times a year, corroding magnificent churches, monuments and the marble walls of elegant villas. The consortium intends to stem the tides with the mobile dikes strung across the bottom of the lagoon entrances. During flood tides, <PERSON> Fabris </PERSON> said, engineers will raise the dikes, effectively sealing the lagoon. Ships will be able to sail in and out through a series of locks at the entrances. `` With the mobile system we will be able to decide at what point and at what time we want to intervene,'' said <PERSON> Fabris </PERSON>. Flood tides are triggered by differences in atmospheric pressure at either end of the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> or by the sirocco wind blowing across the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> and up the <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION>, driving the sea water northward toward <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>. Great flood tides were heavily destructive to <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> in 789, in 1268 and in 1280. In 1410, they killed close to 1,000 people. In this century, the worst floods came in 1916, 1936, 1951 and in 1966, when high water caused an estimated $ 85 million damage. Venetians have struggled for centuries to protect the city from its surroundings. These efforts have included building sea walls to guard the littoral islands and several anti-silting projects. More recently they succeeded in stopping <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> from sinking, after it had settled 4 -LCB- inches from 1926 to 1970, by banning industrial use of underground water. Critics say the government and the new consortium have reacted slowly to <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s problems, that the city has been drowning in a sea of bureacracy and empty talk. The consortium's <PERSON> Fabris </PERSON> responds that the law creating the project requires that all the work be `` experimentally tested, reversible if necessary and done in stages.'' Scientists used satellite analysis and computer models to study how their work will effect the problems of stagnation and erosion. Scale models of the entire lagoon and the three entrances were built at <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s hydraulic experimental center in nearby <LOCATION> Padua </LOCATION>. In September, workers will install the prototype of one of the 56-foot-high, 66-foot-long mobile dikes for six to eight months of tests. <PERSON> Fabris </PERSON> said the consortium will be ready to put the entire line of dikes in place by 1992. He added that the tests indicate that engineers will be able to help wash pollutants out of the lagoon. As part of the project, the government is also supposed to enact laws restricting the dumping of industrial pollutants and the use of agricultural pesticides that seep into the lagoon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Aug. 2</NOTE>
