<HEAD>Syrians Seek to Save Damascus' Old City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Coppersmiths and carpenters still clatter today at their ancient crafts along the `` Street called Straight,'' where the Bible says <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was cured of blindness. Venders peddle vials of perfume beneath Roman columns near the great 8th century Omayyed mosque. Stalls in the narrow market streets still dazzle with spices, silver and silk in the city that <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON>, scourge of the Crusaders, called home. Some of <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>'s old city survives, but it is in danger of being swallowed by the sprawl of modern <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. `` You ca n't imagine how important <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> is, and how rich,'' said <PERSON> Afif </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahnassi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s Director of Antiquities. He's one of about a dozen officials and experts named this year to a committee charged with saving the flavor and heritage of this ancient city, termed `` the Paradise of the Orient'' by the 12th century Spanish traveller <PERSON> Ibn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jubayer </PERSON>. Busy streets now flank the old Roman walls, and mud-sided 19th century neighborhoods nearby have fallen to highways and modern housing needed for a growing metropolis of 3 million people. Even within the old walled city, `` we're afraid ... there's now some opinion to remove the old houses,'' <PERSON> Bahnassi </PERSON> said in an interview. The committee has set conditions on development and is working to restore old neighborhoods. <PERSON> Bahnassi </PERSON> said it has asked owners to restore their own buildings, and offers financial assistance for those who need help. But he said it is difficult to find craftsmen skilled in the old buildings' styles. `` We'd like to encourage the workers to be more interested in the old systems,'' he said. Damascenes often refer to their city as the oldest still inhabited, but its age is uncertain. Settlements excavated nearby date to about 10,000 B.C. <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> itself is referred to in Egyptian and other documents dating back about 4,000 years, <PERSON> Bahnassi </PERSON> said. Arameans who migrated to the city from the deserts built a temple to the god <PERSON> Haddad </PERSON> in about 1,000 B.C. The Romans used the same site for their temple to <LOCATION> Jupiter </LOCATION>. Early Christians built a cathedral on the Roman foundations, and elements of both remain in in the richly decorated Omayyed mosque, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s oldest surviving monumental mosque. Among its shrines is one holding the head of <PERSON> John </PERSON> the Baptist, revered by Moslems as well as Christians. According to Acts 9 in the New Testament, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, then <PERSON> Saul </PERSON>, was stricken blind as he made his way to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> to persecute the followers of Christ. He was taken to a house on the `` Street called Straight,'' the account goes on. It says <PERSON> Ananias </PERSON>, a follower of Christ, was instructed by a voice from Heaven to find <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> there and cure him of his blindness. Nearly all the great empires of Middle Eastern history fought over and conquered <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, whose oasis straddles three enduring trade routes connecting <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mesopotamia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Early Islamic authorities referred to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>' oasis as the site of the Garden of Eden. `` The Gardens encircle it like the halo round the moon,'' <PERSON> Ibn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jubayer </PERSON> wrote in the 12th century. Some say <PERSON> Cain </PERSON> slew <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> on the slopes of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kassioun </LOCATION> on the city's Western edge, and placed <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>'s birthplace there. At the height of its glory under the Islamic Omayyed dynasty, <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> was the capital of an Arab empire that reached from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> to the edges of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Yet despite its many wars, `` nobody in its history destroyed it completely,'' said <PERSON> Harb </PERSON> <PERSON> Farzat </PERSON>, an historian at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Damascus </ORGANIZATION>. The crowded streets and bazaars of the old city still conjure images of medieval times. Upper stories project over the narrow lanes, often nearly touching. Crumbling walls on some reveal the mud, wattle and wood construction <PERSON> Ibn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jubayer </PERSON> noted in 1184, when <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON> used the city as his capital during his successful campaign against the Crusaders of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. Ornate stone doorways open onto the luxurious marble floors and fountains of restored Turkish baths, some dating to the 13th century and still in use. Coffee houses hundreds of years old still serve thick, heavily sugared Turkish coffee to men in Arab garb who puff at waterpipes over games of backgammon. But <PERSON> Farzat </PERSON>, who was born in the city, said: `` When you've seen <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> a generation before, you can see how it has changed.'' From a high-rise hotel window, he pointed at the sprawl of concrete now covering the ghouta, the oasis gardens that led many ancient authors to liken <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> to paradise. The greatest loss, he said, was `` to destroy the ghouta, the Paradise of <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>. Now it's covered with buildings.''
</TEXT>
