<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Aug. 4 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Refugees Await Outcome of Stalemated Polisario War</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TINDOUF, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sea of faded-green tents has become home for 165,000 refugees _ mostly women, children and old men _ of a stalemated war in the desert of nearby <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. Four-color flags of the self-proclaimed Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic flutter in the hot wind, over banners and grafitti proclaiming the republic's slogan: `` The Entire Homeland or Martyrdom.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and international relief organizations have been feeding and housing the refugees for more than a decade. The refugees wait here in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> for something to happen in the war between <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and the Marxist-led Polisario guerrilla movement for control of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, formerly <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. The Algeria-backed Polisario movement set up the <LOCATION> Sahrawi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> republic </LOCATION> in 1976 after <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> turned <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> over to <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> _ the latter has since withdrawn. Although the Sahrawi republic won diplomatic recognition from more than 70 countries, mostly in the Third World, it has been unable to gain a permanent foothold in the mineral-rich territory. The war has reached a stalemate and the guerrillas now talk of a compromise settlement, but prospects seem distant and sporadic fighting continues. Polisario officials contend the refugees in camps near this Algerian oasis represent virtually the entire population of the disputed territory. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> held the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> until 1975, mainly to protect the nearby <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canary </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. Little effort was made to develop the wilderness, an area about the size of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. Spanish colonial records indicate the territory had a population of only 75,000 when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> pulled out. At least 50,000 now live under Moroccan rule, frequently proclaiming their loyalty to <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> II. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> maintains that more than three-fourths of the Tindouf refugees are not from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> but from neighboring <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION> and other impoverished countries on the fringes of the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION>. Arabic-speaking Moslems, they originally were nomads, herding goats and camels over unmarked boundaries, often not even aware which country they were in. <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, a high-school pupil studying in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, spoke of the culture shock he experiences in traveling between the dual worlds of modern <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> and his family tent near <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION>. `` I live in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> nine months of the year and I hate it and long for my family,'' he said, sitting recently in the brightly decorated tent beside his younger sister, <PERSON> Habiba </PERSON>. `` Then when I come here for the three months of the summer, I'm dying to return.'' He shares his perplexity with hundreds of young people who travel to universities in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Polisario officials have set up a system to prevent loss of a national and cultural identity among the young and to reinforce their motivation to fight. `` The young teach the old how to read and write,'' said <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON>, a school teacher. `` The old teach them history and tradition so as to enforce their sense of identity.'' From age 9, the children also receive basic military training in preparation for automatic conscription after high school of boys who do n't go on to university. <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION>, a military zone, is 1,000 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. The refugee camps begin about two miles west of <LOCATION> Tindouf </LOCATION>, their rows of canvas tents and adjacent stone kitchens spread in clusters over the stark landscape. At a camp hospital, Dr. <PERSON> Khadigetto </PERSON> <PERSON> Alawi </PERSON> said she had just returned from five years of medical training in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. She said she and the other hospital staff receive no salaries. Polisario officials said no one receives any pay, including the 16,000-man guerrilla army and 70,000 officials. A few raise goats and sheep for their own use, they said. A woman who identified herself as <PERSON> Humayed </PERSON> welcomed a group of visiting reporters into the tent she shares with six women and children of her family. She said their menfolk were `` at the front'' 120 miles away. `` The women have an important role while the men are away at war,'' said a Roman Catholic priest who goes by the name <PERSON> Father </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON> and works for the <LOCATION> Caritas </LOCATION> relief organization. `` They marry young, so as to have many children. And they also undergo military training themselves. We try to teach them the importance of mother-child care. They concentrate a lot on preventive medicine.'' A Polisario official said it is expected that young war widows remarry quickly in order to maintain population growth. Ghalouha el-Salm, a war widow-bride, said she has spent the nine years since she lost her husband rearing a daughter but now is marrying again. `` I have to continue having children,'' she said, explaining that it was a `` national'' requirement. Most of the women said they long to return to the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> and its cool <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> breezes when the war is over.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Aug. 4</NOTE>
