<HEAD>U.S. Drug Policy Angers Caribbean Allies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jamaica-Marijuana, b0281</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT release date at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's crackdown on drug trafficking is upsetting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. They complain the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is maligning their leaders and encroaching on their sovereignty. `` It's just unsettling to people to hear that their leaders have been charged in a court in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> when anyone who knows anything about justice knows these cases will never come up for a hearing,'' said Prime Minister <PERSON> Eugenia </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>. `` It's not only wrong, its incomprehensible.'' The issue came up at a recent meeting of the leaders of 13 former and current <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> colonies in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, in <LOCATION> Antigua-Barbuda </LOCATION>. The young parliamentary democracies, most of which gained independence over the past 25 years, drafted a letter to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> protesting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug policy in the region. The contents of the letter were not disclosed, but it was believed to have focused on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investigations of government leaders in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, as well as Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the Panamanian strongman. Sir <PERSON> Lynden </PERSON> <PERSON> Pindling </PERSON>, prime minister of the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, is under investigation by a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> grand jury for alleged drug-related offenses. He has denied any connection with the drug trade. At the <ORGANIZATION> Caricom </ORGANIZATION> summit, <PERSON> Pindling </PERSON> assailed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for what he called its `` ideologically motivated, interventionist'' policies. In March, Col. <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> was indicted by a federal grand jury for allegedly conspiring to import cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, a key figure in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s army, denied any involvement. In May, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee heard testimony by a convicted drug trafficker that linked Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> with payoffs. An incensed <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, whose marijuana eradication program is the most comprehensive in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s history, filed a formal complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which later said the testimony was unsubstantiated and baseless. `` People are concerned with the reputation of individuals,'' said Prime Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Esquivel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION>. `` I'm referring to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> witnesses that are free to commit libel ... and those people who are libeled have no protection or recourse.'' Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Antigua </LOCATION> accused the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration of exporting its battle against drugs to win votes for Republicans in November. `` The domestic imperatives of an election year in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have forced certain people ... to step beyond what is acceptable in terms of ... the sovereignty of a country,'' he said. Prime Minister A.N.R. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Trinidad-Tabago </PERSON> suggested that countries work out ways to bring offenders to justice and ensure that `` individuals are not just slandered and characters assassinated ... or that countries should use the judicial process for political ends.''
