<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   07-25 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0597</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday July 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Only the Numbers Add Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like good comedians, certain investment analysts never run out of material. As one respected member of that fraternity observed earlier this month, they followed the monetarists in the early 1980s, switched to oil-watching in 1985 and jumped to commodities last year. `` And now _ drumroll please _ it is the meteorologists,'' observes <PERSON> Lucinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Mezy </PERSON>, director of equity research <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a bank-holding company based in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The drought, that is, has developed brand new commentaries on where the economy is headed. Billions of words have come from brokerage houses on what the drought means for food prices, and therefore for stocks. The political activities of 1988 provide myriad variations for commentaries on interest rates, inflation, stock prices and investor confidence. Each poll, whether or not it shows changes, is reason again for further commentary. The Iran-Iraq affair already has been worked into forecasts by analysts who could not think of anything more to say about <PERSON> Nicarauga </PERSON> and the rest of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and by bulls who had run out of things to say about glasnost. Fallback resources include the emergence of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as an industrial power, the amount of money in circulation, the budget and trade deficits, the dollar, the possibility of inflation or higher interest rates and Third World debt. Increasingly, analysts analyze analysts, producing one of the oddest of all analyses, one that states the stock market is about to rise when the majority of analysts are bearish, and is set to fall when they turn bullish. There is an open pit mine, ready to be worked at any time, in analyzing the disposition of investors. Do they have confidence? Do they have money? Will they buy cars and appliances? Will they save? Will they buy junk bonds? Government provides enough material, often in controversial form, to keep armies of analysts computing and dissecting. Lists of upcoming government economic announcements has become a regular feature of brokers' letters. A rise or fall in housing starts is good for hundreds of words on the consequences to securities. Inflation and interest rates, jobless statistics, factory capacity, imports, exports, debt, deficits all go into the mix. Still, without these events, institutions and subjects there would hardly be a drought of material on which to comment. Always, there is the mine of statistical material that can be dug up and massaged by computer. That resource was well used and thoroughly abused in the weeks and months immediately following the securities crash of last October, the most common of the analyses producing statistics likening it to the Great Crash of 1929. It mattered little that events failed to prove that 1987 was 1929 all over again; it simply provided more material for analysis on why the two years differed. In themselves, differences of opinion are fodder for analysis. How all this helps investors is difficult to perceive, but it is easy enough to see how it helps those who sell securities. It keeps customers talking. It maintains interest. It provides material for sales calls. But almost if not utterly lost in the mountain of commentary is the matter of accuracy. It is then that the words are seen for what they are worth. In investing, those words just do not add up. Only the numbers do.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues July 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
