<SECOND>AM-Chile-Journalist, Adv 01,0929</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, Aug. 1, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Prize-Winning Chilean Journalist Lives with Fear and Harassment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> goes to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in September to receive a prize for courageous reporting she'll have to get permission from a Chilean court. Pending against her are charges of criminally slandering President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and the armed forces he commands. By law she must get approval to go abroad, but she brushes that aside as just a minor annoyance compared to periodic arrests, two stints in prison and daily death threats in the four years since she took on what she calls `` the holy trinity'' _ <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, his family and the military. Her articles accusing <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and his right-wing government of abuse of power were cited by <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Nieman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in awarding her this year's <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyon </PERSON> <PERSON> Prize </PERSON>. It praised her `` courage in reporting objectively and honestly ... despite the government's efforts to silence her.'' She plans to travel to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to accept the award Sept. 15, but with a certain chagrin. `` There are lots of -LRB- Chilean -RRB- journalists who are facing legal charges, but most are n't as famous as I,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, 38, said in an interview. `` This bothers me a lot sometimes.'' According to the local <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s human rights office, more than 30 journalists face criminal slander charges lodged by the government. They include Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>' boss, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, director of the leftist magazine <PERSON> Analisis </PERSON>. He was convicted of offending the armed forces and is serving 541 nights in a jail cell. He is at liberty during the daytime. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> cites the existence of Analisis and several other opposition publications as proof that <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has freedom of the press. But according to Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, `` There's a very high cost. It's a cost you pay every day.'' She said her telephone rings constantly with death threats, that cars full of armed men regularly park outside her home, that a dead cat was once tossed into her yard. `` Certainly I'm afraid.'' she said. `` I'm afraid they'll kill me. But I've made a choice. I've taken a path of no return.'' The choice was made in late 1983, she said, when she began working for another opposition magazine, <LOCATION> Cauce </LOCATION>. At the time, a wave of anti-Pinochet protests obliged the government to somewhat relax its strict control of the news media. In early 1984, the magazine published the first of a series of investigative reports by Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> alleging corruption by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> and members of his family and brutal human rights abuse by the military. The articles, which presented documentation and detail, established her reputation as one of the country's best opposition journalists and shattered a powerful taboo. `` We broke a sacrosanct rule that existed in the opposition press: do n't mention <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, his family or the armed forces. This is the holy trinity,'' she said. In the years since, Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> has been arrested 10 times and imprisoned twice in connection with her reporting. Her first imprisonment was in July 1984. She said she was put in a small, exposed cell in a maximum-security punishment block occupied by about 20 common criminals who had led a prison riot three months earlier. Many still wore bandages on their wounds. She was the first woman they had seen since being isolated, and regularly beaten, after the riot, she said. They filled the hall outside her cell, screaming and pressing against the bars while they exposed themselves and performed obscene acts. The bars were thin, and she feared they would cave in. `` It went on all night long,'' she said. `` I did n't think I was going to be able to stand it. It was very terrible.'' The next morning, at her tearful insistence, she was moved to a section for woman political prisoners. She spent six days there before being released. She would return in October 1987, for 22 days, after publishing an interview with an opposition leader, <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, who sharply criticized <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. The case sent chills through the Chilean jouralistic community and prompted denunciations from press organizations around the world. Although the interview was published in textual, question-and-answer form, Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> _ and not <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON> _ was charged with slandering the president. Government prosecutors said she was responsible because she served as the vehicle for his remarks. The case remains pending, as do two others, in which she is accused of slandering a military prosecutor and the armed forces in general. Five previous cases against her have ended in acquittal. She said she considers her most important story a series of interviews in late 1984 with a deserter from the secret police who recounted the torture and killing of 15 leftists. Some were old friends of hers, she said. In seeking confirmation of the deserter's tale, she sought the help of a human rights activist, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrada </PERSON>, and a Communist who survived detention by the secret police, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Parrada </PERSON> and <PERSON> Guerrero </PERSON>, along with a third man, <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> <PERSON> Nattino </PERSON>, were found dead with their throats slashed in March 1985. `` Why they let me live, I do n't know,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said. `` Here they punish journalists who make terrible denunciations: murders, torture, disappearances, corruption. But they do n't investigate the actions being denounced That's hard for me to accept.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs Aug. 1</NOTE>
