<FIRST>a i AM-Egypt-Bricks Adv02   07-25 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Bricks, Adv 02,0765</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday AMs, Aug. 2, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Egyptians Shut Down Brick Factories to Save Fertile Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIZA, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fertile soil is sparse in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> _ just 6 million acres along the Nile _ and the government is cracking down on those who use it to make bricks. At a brickyard here one recent day, workers swarmed like bees over a kiln as they dismantled a brickyard that had fallen victim to the government order. The government's intend is to preserve <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s arable land to help feed an exploding population _ now 53 million and growing at a rate of 1.2 million a year. After five years of loose application of a law banning the use of fertile topsoil to make bricks, the government in December set a six-month deadline and recently sent police out to see that an estimated 1,700 affected brickyards indeed close down. `` We admit that this is the first time the law has been effective,'' said <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaki </PERSON>, head of the department responsible for land protection at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` The owners realized that we were serious this time and all the brickyards stopped functioning on deadline without violence.'' The decree requires brickyard owners to switch from the age-old process of making bricks by hand with topsoil to a mechanized one that makes bricks only with pure clay, thus eliminating the use of topsoil. Violators of the topsoil ban face six months in prison and a fine. Officials acknowledged that the decree has troublesome side-effects: a growing black market in bricks and unemployment for about 70,000 workers. Only 41 of the dismantled brickyards so far have switched to the mechanized method, at a cost the equivalent in Egyptian pounds of $ 13,000 to $ 650,000, <PERSON> Zaki </PERSON> said. He added that 200 others were expected to follow suit. `` At the moment, the price of bricks is rising steeply because of the law enforcement,'' said <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramez </PERSON>, responsible for building-material control at the Housing Ministry. He said black market prices of the machine-produced bricks are double the official $ 30 for 1,000. `` We expect to have a complete balance between supply and demand within five years,'' <PERSON> Ramez </PERSON> added. The enforcement of the law, he said, has resulted in a shortage of 2 billion to 3 billion bricks this year. Officials estimate that about 4,500 acres of arable land have become unproductive in the last 20 years because topsoil was stripped for bricks. The loss is considerable for a country that produces only 40 percent of its food and must import the rest to feed its burgeoning population. `` Some people used to remove earth down to 10 meters -LRB- 30 feet -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Zaki </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` Any removal weakens the soil, taking away essential nutrients, and raises the water table. `` We are requiring owners to reclaim their land _ at a cost of 10,000 to 15,000 pounds -LRB- $ 4,300 to $ 6,500 -RRB- per acre,'' <PERSON> Zaki </PERSON> said. He estimated this would take at least two years. The removal of topsoil began in the early 1970s after the High Dam at <LOCATION> Aswan </LOCATION> went into operation and held back flood waters bearing tons of silt that originally was used in the brick industry. As construction boomed in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the demand for bricks sky-rocketed, some farmers abandoned their crops to make as much as 70 times more money by selling topsoil or making bricks on their own. `` Earth bricks brought us enormous profits,'' said <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu-Rawash </PERSON>, a former brickyard owner in <LOCATION> Giza </LOCATION>. `` In a good month I would make 3,000 pounds -LRB- $ 1,300 -RRB- with earth from one of my acres.'' He maintained that `` no harm is done to land scraped two meters -LRB- about six feet -RRB- deep; anything can be planted on it.'' <PERSON> Abu-Rawash </PERSON> has switched to raising cattle and has turned most of his brickyard into a banana plantation, which he said brings only a quarter of the profit he made from bricks. His employees, whose numbers have been trimmed from 50 to 20, were busy one recent day dismantling one kiln with 22 others to be taken down in the neighborhood. They were worried about their future. `` This is my first day of work since all the brickyards shut down last month,'' <PERSON> Abdel-Hamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharafeddin </PERSON> said. `` I will work on the other kilns and then who knows? People like me are pushed aside. I know nothing but brickmaking.''
</TEXT>
