<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, Aug. 5, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Land Reform Changing El Salvador's Countryside</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Land reform, the most radical and expensive government project in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s history, has benefited more than half a million people since its inception in 1980 and is radically changing the social structure of the countryside. Despite major shortcomings, the program has redistributed 30 percent of the country's arable land, after compensating former owners. The 520,000 people who have received land, either as individuals or members of cooperatives, make up a quarter of the country's rural poor. The program, however, is beset by such problems as flagging production, tight credit, deficient administration and alleged corruption. It is also hampered by <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s guerrilla war. Land reform was designed, principally by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, as a means of undercutting the leftist guerrillas in their efforts to win the sympathy of the rural poor. A dozen government and military officials, cooperativists, peasants and international development officials interviewed said while the toughest years of land reform are past, obstacles remain in extending it and ensuring its smooth running. `` Some former landowners have not abandoned the idea of recovering their lands and, with them, real power. They recall with nostalgia their wealth,'' said <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Salvadoran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agrarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transformation </ORGANIZATION>, the government body primarily responsible for land reform. But he added that the vast majority of the former owners have accepted compensation, and that title to the property has been legally transferred. The process has cost almost $ 300 million, most of it provided by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Agrarian reform is enshrined in the 1983 constitution, which would have to be scrapped if big holdings were to again be concentrated in few hands. Some left-of-center cooperativists and officials of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are concerned that the right wing, which won control of the legislature in March elections, might try to undo some of the reform. The rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, known as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, is considered in a good position to challenge the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> in presidential elections scheduled for March. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Arevalo </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lands </ORGANIZATION>, said a marked increase has been noted in expulsions of land reform beneficiaries in recent months. He blames former owners emboldened by <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s legislative victory and prospects for gaining the presidency next year. `` Most landholders are licensed to carry arms,'' <PERSON> Arevalo </PERSON> said. `` The former owners, who have always opposed the reform, are now encouraged and are fighting the campesinos politically, juridically and by force.'' But he said virtually all of the 500 or so recent expulsions were from small holdings and represent a tiny percentage of the reformed sector. He said the government is resorting to the courts and the military to get the small farmers reinstated. He noted, however, that the judiciary has been dominated for decades by the rightwingers who might favor the landowners. Phase I of land reform expropriated all holdings over 1,235 acres, involving 477 properties owned by 262 families. A subsequent Land-to-the-Tiller law affected small holdings and benefited about 45,000 families. The Phase I lands were converted into 329 cooperatives, 25 of which have been abandoned because they are in war zones. About 30,000 families live and work on the 304 Phase I cooperatives. According to <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> and international development officials working with the reform, a third of the cooperatives are able to finance operations, pay debts and dividends to their members. Another third are described as bankrupt `` basket cases'' that can not succeed in their current structure. The remaining third are described as borderline. <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s platform calls for the dismantling of all but the most successful cooperatives, dividing the unsuccessful and borderline ventures into parcels that would be transferred by title to the farmers working them. The party contends that only by converting <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> into `` a country of property owners'' will there be sufficient incentive and initiative to spur production. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, after seeing many millions of dollars lost, have already begun dividing up the failed cooperatives into family plots. `` The political decision is to divide,'' said <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>. One divided venture is the 2,100-acre <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Normandia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cooperative </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Usulutan </LOCATION> province 65 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Before being expropriated from <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> in 1980, it produced cotton for export, with small sections dedicated to the corn and beans consumed by the peasants who worked it. Two months into this year's growning season, with abundant rains after two years of drought, it is a green sea of thigh-high corn divided in 8.5-acre plots. It is home for 170 families who live in mud-brick tile-roofed houses with wells but without running water or electricity. It has a school but no clinic. A mile into the fields along an oxen-trod path, <PERSON> Marcial </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> worked with his wife <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> and two of their eight children, tending tomato plants along the edge of their plot, most of which was sown with corn. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> talked of his years in the land-reform program. `` From'80 to'86 we had credit from the government and we planted cotton. But we only showed losses. Those who are up in arms -LRB- the guerrillas -RRB- would attack each year right before we were going to spray, and destroy or damage the plants. Without pesticide, the crop was always bad,'' he said. Part of the guerrillas' strategy is to sabotage of the national economy, which is heavily dependent on exports of coffee, sugar and cotton. The cooperative decided last year to divide the land into family plots, leaving some fallow and some to be rented or parceled out to eventual new beneficiaries of the agricultural reform. Asked if he'd prefer to continue working as part of a cooperative or have title to his plot, <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> responded: `` Both ways are good. Individually, if we have financing, we would probably make the land produce more. But the cooperative could also produce good results under better conditions, and it would provide more work for more people.'' The cooperative is considered one of the `` basket-cases.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 5</NOTE>
