<FIRST>s a BC-APN--MerchantMarine-History Adv07   07-25 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Merchant Marine-History, Adv07,0626</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Merchant Marine</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The decline of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchant marine seems all the more notable in a nation with an illustrious seagoing past. In its birth and infancy, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was basically an island. You had to take a boat to get there. Ships were the highways of the Colonies. Seamen, still boys, `` came up the hawsepipe'' to learn before the mast. <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowditch </PERSON>, the great navigator, got his start selling pulleys and marlin spikes as a young ship chandler until he learned enough ropes to go to sea. Young lads from <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> shipped out on whalers across the globe, came home after years and signed on again as mates. Whalers lit the lamps of a young nation. Slavers in their vile trade populated the cotton fields. Ship-borne immigrants populated the whole country. Fast American-designed clippers from <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> out-sped the world around the Horn in the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> trade. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON> drove the first practicable steamboat on the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in 1789, 20 years before <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulton </PERSON>. -LRB- <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON> also demonstrated he was ahead of his time by dying of a morphine overdose. -RRB- In 1806 <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> Tudor </PERSON> displayed <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> maritime ingenuity by eschewing <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> as `` a place for loafers like all colleges'' and exporting around the world what wintry <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> had plenty of: ice. The tide began turning in the 1840s when <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> subsidized the new Cunard Line on the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> run. In 1847 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> followed suit by subsidizing building ships for the <ORGANIZATION> Bremen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, jointly owned by Americans and the city-state of <LOCATION> Bremen </LOCATION>. Carrying the flag became national policy and pride. In <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, shippers were thus over the years alternately lulled and starved by congressional and presidential whim with the purse strings. The real deep-six was epitomized by the man <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Braynard </PERSON>, curator of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Kings </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, calls `` that wretch, <PERSON> Horace </PERSON> <PERSON> Greeley </PERSON>,'' when he advised <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s young men to go West They did, ironically in prairie schooners. A nation turned its back on its ocean heritage. `` The seaman changed from the town hero to the local drifter,'' says <PERSON> Braynard </PERSON>, a steam-fired advocate of a return to maritime greatness. `` The need for labor in the Unitred States was so great any loose men were drawn to jobs in the heartland.'' Never again would an increasingly rich <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> be able to match the low wages, often heavily subsidized, of foreign merchantmen. The glory days were largely done. In the century after the Civil War, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> built only 10 liners for the lucrative <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> passenger business. Not that know-how did n't exist. In World War II, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> built 6,000 ships, a third of the world's merchant fleet, to defeat <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Using assembly line techniques, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> yard built a 10,000-ton Liberty Ship in just over three days. But at the end of the war the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which by then had almost half of the world's tonnage, gave away much of its fleet to its stricken allies, a nice thing to do, particularly for some wily Greeks with names like <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Niarchos </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Yanks </ORGANIZATION> did not lose their ingenuity. <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> started the container ship revolution with the bright idea of putting truck trailers on the unused deck space of a coastal tanker. Americans invented the ship that loads and unloads itself with its own lighters. `` Then the whole world zapped us with our own ideas,'' says <PERSON> Braynard </PERSON>, his exasperation at full ahead.
</TEXT>
