<FIRST>s a BC-APN--DeafInmates Adv07   07-25 0983</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Deaf Inmates, Adv07,1011</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Is a child who is hard of hearing more likely to become a criminal later in life? Studies in the nation's prisons suggest there is a link. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> is one researcher who believes that dealing with hearing disorders in young children may help reduce crime.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Noting an unusually high percentage of prisoners who are hard of hearing _ almost half in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> _ some researchers suspect the disorder may contribute to criminal behavior. `` My working hypothesis is that hearing loss may be the first link in a chain of events or circumstances that eventually lead to a life of crime,'' says <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communicative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disorders </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> found that 48.5 percent of the inmates at the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Parchman </LOCATION> suffer some kind of hearing disorder compared with only 7 percent among the general public. The statistics are even more startling because the 7 percent represents the entire general population from infants to the elderly. However, the average age of the prison population is 25, and the younger age group should have a lower percentage of hearing disorders. Other researchers have had similar findings. An <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION> study in 1970 indicated 40 percent of the inmates had hearing disorders, a 1986 study in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> cited 36 percent and a 1979 study in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> 17 percent. The ultimate question, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says, is: `` What impact has the hearing loss had on that person's life? Has that hearing loss in any way contributed, directly or indirectly, to the person's criminal behavior and how do you determine that? <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>'s research team, which includes an audiologist, psychologist, psychiatrist, medical doctor and linguist, is now applying to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for a grant for a five-year, follow-up study. The second study will determine the severity, nature and causes of inmates' hearing disorders. He said the amount of the request has yet to be worked out. Corrections officials as well as audiologists and speech pathologists nationwide are concerned about the high level of hearing disorders among prison populations, says <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, manager of audiology and technical assistance for the American <ORGANIZATION> Speech-Language-Hearing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rockville </LOCATION>, Md. The 56,000-member organization is the largest association of audiologists and speech and language pathologists in the nation. The association called for more research in the field after a task force's cursory look at the problem in 1984. The task force cited a nationwide survey of about 200 state and federal corrections administrators which indicated 77 percent of those polled believe the psychological and communication problems stemming from hearing disorders lead to criminal behavior. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says he has found only a few dozen studies conducted in the past 40 years on any aspect of prisoners' hearing and speech disorders. Of the few studies available, he says, almost all have merely documented the prevalence of problems. If the hearing disorder is congenital or occurred early in the inmate's life, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says, it's likely the handicap helped shape a criminal personality. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>'s initial research in 1985 did n't indicate the exact nature, severity, or causes of the hearing disorders because there was n't enough money for detailed hearing tests or medical evaluations. The initial study involved merely testing each <LOCATION> Parchman </LOCATION> inmate's hearing at different frequencies and comparing that to a normal person's hearing range <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> compares the initial auditory screening test to a simple eye chart used by an opthalmologist. The doctor knows the patient ca n't see the letters at a certain size, but more tests are needed for a diagnosis of the problem. There could be many causes for the hearing disorders, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says, including heredity and loud noises as well as lack of medical attention to ear infections or other problems in childhood. Even relatively minor hearing losses could damage a child's personality development, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says Many children with undetected hearing disorders grow up without ever knowing they're physically different from their peers. However, they must deal with considerably more stress and disorientation. `` It may sound like mumbling,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says. `` It would be like you trying to interact with someone with a very heavy foreign accent. If you have to listen to them for a long time, it will tire you out. You have to channel and focus your attention to comprehend.'' The strain may make the child irritable, and he may appear to have an extremely short attention span. Some children with undetected hearing losses may grow up able to capture words, but the emotions attached to the words escape them, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says. `` Consider a preschool child who has a hearing loss. Not a real terrible hearing loss. The child learns to talk, but it is severe enough that the child has trouble hearing the meaning of things,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says. `` Not only do you hear what is said. But you hear how it's said. You hear inflections, things like that. You can read my moods and emotions.'' An inability to follow the emotional trains of thought of others could trigger all kinds of anti-social tendencies, <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says. Add the emotional and intellectual handicaps from a hearing disorder to the underprivileged status of many children and you get a prime candidate for prison, he says. `` If that scenario is sometimes correct, theoretically we can sometimes prevent crime by dealing with hearing problems and language problems at a preschool age,'' he says. Some preschool programs such as Head Start do some hearing screening, but many children do n't have hearing tests until kindergarten or much later _ after personality traits are long entrenched. `` I did n't have my first hearing test until I got back from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
