<FIRST>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv07   07-25 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv07,0950</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is quick to point out that much has changed in the South since the filming of the 1967 movie, `` In the Heat of the Night,'' starring <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Poitier </PERSON>. In the new <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> series based on the movie, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> stars as <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON>, police chief of the small <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Sparta </LOCATION>, the role which earned <PERSON> Steiger </PERSON> an Academy Award as best actor. On TV, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rollins </PERSON> co-stars as <PERSON> Virgil </PERSON> <PERSON> Tibbs </PERSON>, whose appointment as <ORGANIZATION> Sparta </ORGANIZATION>'s black chief of detectives causes a stir in the Deep South town. `` I'm playing this different from <PERSON> Rod </PERSON>,'' says <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, the man best remembered as <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> in `` All in the Family.'' `` <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> played it as Southern police chiefs were in 1967. He deserved his Oscar. Remember the news pictures coming out of the South at that time, with the dogs and the fire hoses. But this is 1988. A lot has happened in the South since then. The old attitude no longer works. `` So the chief is fundamentally still the same, but he knows he has to make accommodations. It's against the law to discriminate against black people and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> is going to make sure the law is obeyed. He's a man in conflict. He learned racism at his mother's knee, but he lives by the law and he respects the law.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is holding court at a table designated by a brass plaque as `` <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>'s Corner,'' in the Ginger Man, the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> restaurant he has owned for the past 11 years in partnership with actor <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON>. There's a telephone nearby and people stop by to speak to him. Some wave from the sidewalk outside. He's wearing a light-colored summer suit and a bow tie. His hair is snow white, and his eyes, behind his glasses, are a piercing blue. He picks up a pipe and lights up before continuing: `` In the future we're not going to concentrate so much on the crime. You can find that on every police show. We want to show what crime does to the community and what it does to the policemen, and how two men from very different backgrounds feel about it. The white police chief and the black detective have fundamental differences. They have different sentiments, and although crime affects them in different ways they can work together. `` I think that eluded us in the first outing, but I think we'll get it this time People will say it's right on, which is what they said about ` All in the Family.''' The first season of the show was filmed entirely on location in <LOCATION> Hammond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. But there is talk that the company may go to <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for the fall season to save money. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> says he found the people of <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> cooperative and the city seemed to him to be fully integrated. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON>, and their son, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON>, joined him there. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> also works in his father's restaurant. He says that when he completed `` All in the Family'' in 1983 he was n't looking for a new series. `` I wanted to go to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and do another play,'' he says. `` I did one called ` <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>' and it was a miserable flop. Then I did another, ` Homefront,' and it was a flop, but not a miserable flop. Both plays appealed to the audience but if you do n't get the critic for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> your show folds. What you do is end up putting on a play for just one man.'' He also starred in a CBS movie called `` Brass,'' in which he played the chief of detectives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He says it was not a pilot, but concedes that any TV movie with a star is a de facto pilot. He also starred in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> movie `` The Father Clements Story.'' `` I did n't do any pilots,'' he says, `` although we talked about some. I was all set to do a show with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. I was going to be a kind of old-time <ORGANIZATION> OSS </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> man who's put in charge of a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> defector. We were to have various adventures together. But they gave me a producer who'd had five flops in a row. I said no and they gave me a month to find someone we'd all be satisfied with. I suggested a couple of guys. That was the last I ever heard from them.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is surprised at how fast his latest series came together. His first series, `` All in the Family,'' bounced from network to network and went through several pilots before <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> finally put it on the air in January 1971. It lasted for 12 years. This time, he says, `` I got a call from <PERSON> Freddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> and he asked me to meet him.'' <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> was head of programming at <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> when `` All in the Family'' went on the air. He later became president of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>, then <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, and currently is a successful independent producer. His other shows include <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Matlo