<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Temple of Low Men'' -LRB- Capitol -RRB- _ Crowded House Crowded House's `` Temple of Low Men'' may be the catchiest depressing album you'll ever hear. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> trio, behind <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>'s sprightly <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney-like </PERSON> melodies and some killer hooks, became one of pop music's most gratifying success stories in 1987 with such hits as `` Something So Strong'' and `` Do n't Dream It's Over.'' But do n't look for any silly love songs on the follow-up `` Temple of Low Men.'' <PERSON> Finn </PERSON>'s a brooder, worrying about everything from doomed relationships to his own success. <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> seems especially wary of love on this album's bookends. `` I Feel Possessed'' describes a lover's spellbinding hold on him, but the narrator is as much scared by the power as consumed by it. And `` Better Be Home Soon,'' addressed to an absent lover, is more a threat than a plea. On `` Mansion in the Slums,'' <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> tells everyone who covets his kind of success that it's not worth it. `` The taste of success only lasts you half an hour or less,'' <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> sings. He declares that he'd much rather have a trampoline than an isolation tank in an obvious jibe at the music business's most tortured success, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> Why bother listening to another rock star complaining his life's a mess Because's the music's almost unerringly pretty. `` Better Be Home Soon'' is the kind of lovely ballad <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> used to be able to toss off in his sleep, and the acoustic guitar-based tune will probably benefit commercially from the current singer-songwriter boom. `` Never Be the Same'' and `` I Feel Possessed'' are also particularly strong. There's nothing as instantly accessible as the hits from the first album, but `` Temple of Low Men'' rewards repeated listening. Imagine what Crowded House could do if <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> were happy.
</TEXT>
