<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Minimalism Triumphs for Philip Glass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Minimalist composer <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Glass </PERSON> says his astonishing success in opera over the past decade heralds a return to the spirit of the 1960s. `` I think idealism is something that is becoming acceptable again, if I can put it that way, after a decade of materialism,'' he said. `` The idealism of the'60s, I believe that we're coming back to that,'' he said. `` I think that young people are not all going to be stockbrokers and lawyers. `` I think there's a reaction setting in against that kind of materialism and lack of idealism. And in a way I think that's why we're getting good audiences for these pieces.'' Glass is probably `` the leading contemporary -LRB- opera -RRB- composer of the day,'' said <PERSON> Rheinhard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauly </PERSON>, a music professor and opera historian at <ORGANIZATION> Lewis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION> `` He is one of the few contemporary opera composers who has really developed a strong following. It's unusual for contemporary opera to be really successful.'' Casting simple themes in shimmering repetition and gradual change that fans find entrancing and detractors find stupefying, Glass also has won acclaim in film, theater, dance and other musical modes. In recent years the 51-year-old <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> native has collaborated with singer <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON>, songwriters <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, dance choreographer <PERSON> Twyla </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON> and stage director-designer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. His recent film scores include `` Koyanisqatsi,'' `` Mishima'' and the recently released `` Powaqqatsi.'' Glass was 39 when his first opera, `` <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> on the Beach,'' was performed at the <LOCATION> Avignon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Festival </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1976. His second, `` Satyagraha,'' an account of <PERSON> Mahatma </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s development of the tactic of passive resistance as a young lawyer in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, was commissioned by the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> and performed in <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION> in 1980 `` Akhnaten,'' based on an ancient Egyptian pharaoh and first performed in <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, in 1984, completed a trilogy on `` historical figures who changed the world through the power of their ideas,'' Glass said. All have been sell-outs in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> performances and have been recorded on the CBS Masterworks label. `` Philip Glass operas always sell well,'' said <PERSON> Speight </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, general director of the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have found it -LRB- ` Satyagraha' -RRB- to be the most satisfying of the works,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` I think <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Glass </PERSON> may be writing better music now, but I also think I have never heard a better text with one of his operas.'' In a recent interview during a visit to promote the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> Opera production of `` Satyagraha'' in July, Glass said <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s `` stark idealism ... is one of the reasons why I think younger people are very drawn to this work I think younger people tend to be more idealistic than the older folks. `` <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was a man who was an idealist to the end of his days. He proved ... that idealism is n't something you outgrow. You do n't have to It can be something you can carry with you all your life. That, in itself, is an inspiration.'' The Stuttgart Opera has scheduled performances of `` <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>,'' `` Satyagraha'' and `` Akhnaten'' on successive nights in 1990. `` I think of ` <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>' as being the modern, kind of psychokinetic opera, the one that's amplified and full of energy,'' Glass said. `` It kind of goes with the idea of nuclear energy and progressive ideas in science, right? `` I think of ` Satyagraha' as the lyrical opera, which is all flowing, melodic lines and choruses. There's something very gentle about ` Satyagraha.' It's a lyrical opera. `` I think of ` Akhnaten' as the tragic opera of the three, a very dark one, the one that, at a certain moment, you realize no one gets out of here alive.'' His fourth opera, `` The Making of the Representative From Planet 8'' with a libretto by <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Lessing </PERSON>, premiered in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> on July 8. Performances are scheduled later this year in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. In the script, civilization on another planet is threatened by an ice age. His next, `` The Palace of the Arabian Nights,'' is set for a premiere next year in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and is based `` loosely on the stories of the stories of the Arabian nights,'' Glass said. Last March the Metropolitan Opera gave him a commission for `` The Voyage,'' a three-part allegory based on the exploration of <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Columbus </PERSON>. The premiere is set for October 1992, the 500th anniversary of the sailing of the Pinta, <PERSON> Nina </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Opera `` is the medium of choice for me ... the one in which the composer plays a primary function,'' Glass said. `` The theater is the director's house. The ballet is the choreographer's house. The opera is the composer's house,'' he said. `` I like that.'' From commissioning to staging typically takes three years, he said. `` It takes a year to plan it, a year to write it and a year to build it,'' he said. `` You spend a lot of time involved with your subject, so I am very careful about my subject matter ... they do become part of your life.''
</TEXT>
