<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: ``Love Story'' Author Finds Acclaim With
``Doctors''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> boy who went to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, taught classics at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> and wrote `` Love Story,'' is still juggling serious and popular writing in a leafy corner of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. He looks back on `` Love Story'' as a youthful Camelot, and senses that with his latest novel, `` Doctors,'' he may finally achieve the critical acclaim that has so far eluded him. At 51, he has temporarily given up the rigors of full-time university teaching but remains a fellow at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wolfson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> An occasional sports commentator, he dreams of winning the over-60 category in the 1997 <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> marathon. `` I am today a writer who is lucky enough to have academic privileges at <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>,'' he says. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>'s fifth and most ambitious novel, `` Doctors,'' is the first that did not draw on his own life. Instead it chronicles members of the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> class of 1962, which included several of his friends. He said he tried to tackle the subject of doctors and the pressures they face with the passion of `` Love Story,'' his first novel, and the scope of his last novel, `` The Class,'' a 25-year fictional follow-up of his fellow <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> graduates of 1958. `` For a long while I lived in gossip columns as <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> ` Love Story' Segal,'' he said in an interview. `` People would run up to me in airports and sing the first few bars of the tune from the movie version. It's not such a bad thing. If it had stopped there, I would have looked back on life as an athlete looks back ... and say I was there once.'' Instead, he moved on to such works as `` The Class'' and `` Doctors'' which, at 679 pages, is five times the length of `` Love Story.'' <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> remarks: `` Publishers used to worry that my books were too short. Now they're worrying that they're too long.'' He does n't feel he is an expatriate American writer. The academic world is the same everywhere, he said, and with satellite television and $ 168 fares to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is never far away. `` In this day and age, if I need something from the <LOCATION> Carnegie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delicatessen </LOCATION>, there's always the Concorde,'' he said, `` and it never gets that bad.''. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, is English and when <PERSON> Francesca </PERSON>, their musically gifted 8-year-old daughter, started school, he decided it was unfair to keep commuting between <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>. But he hates <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s weather and hopes to spend winters in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and teach there when <PERSON> Francesca </PERSON> becomes a teen-ager. Academics who have achieved popular success as writers include British philosopher <PERSON> Iris </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> astronomer <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Eco </PERSON>, a professor of semiotics. `` I only hope some day I'll reach the level of scholarship or literary respectability that they've achieved,'' <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> said. `` It gives me a goal to shoot for.'' <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> speaks nine languages and has written a book on Roman comedy and more than 50 articles on Greek tragedy, Latin poetry and ancient athletics. But he has always found time to indulge his love of pop literature. He wrote the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hasty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pudding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> show in 1958 and has written or co-written several screenplays including <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beatles </ORGANIZATION>' `` Yellow Submarine'' in 1968 `` Love Story,'' his bittersweet tale of youthful love and death which has sold more than 20 million copies in 33 languages since publication in 1970, turned the unknown professor into an international celebrity. The sequel, `` <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>'s Story,'' a 1977 best seller, was followed by `` Man, Woman and Child.'' Although he was refused tenure at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> in 1971 _ some say jealous colleagues disdained his success _ <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> kept teaching and writing. In 1981, he returned to <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> as a full professor, though still without tenure, and retired in 1987. To critics who dismissed `` Love Story'' as fluff, he replies: `` Eighteen years later, when I find myself feeling guilty for all that success and thinking ` Love Story' was overrated, I pull out my Encyclopedia Britannica and see myself listed as writing in the tradition of the classic sentimental novelists, and then my ego relights. `` It was my little Camelot and it ca n't be taken away. It was my idyll. `` But fortunately, I got my second wind or second chance with ` The Class.' I had exhausted the possibilities of the sentimental novel and I got into the saga business, which has vastly more raw material.'' `` The Class,'' a 1985 best seller, was <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>'s first novel to receive modest critical acclaim, winning literary prizes in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. `` I actually thought ` The Class' was the end, because I'd written my life story into it, split apart,'' he said. He had qualms about writing `` Doctors,'' doubting his ability to enter their world. He spent two years attending medical congresses, talking to doctors and wandering through <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> weaing a white coat and a badge identifying him as Dr. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>. `` It says in little letters ` professor of Latin,' so I could walk the halls,'' said <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, who has a doctorate in comparative literature. Why doctors? `` Because they're very special,'' he said. `` They're the people we fear, need, love and hate the most. ... And they are answerable, so they think, only to God.'' He says he set out to write a diatribe against unscrupulous doctors, but met so many dedicated ones that he had to stop himself from going the other way. An insomniac, <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> normally works from 4 a.m. to 5 p.m. without leaving his desk. Then the slightly built athlete, who has completed over 40 marathons, goes for a swim or a run. <PERSON> Segal </PERSON> says he is writing one more academic book, a history of classical comedy, but his next novel depends on what happens to `` Doctors.'' The first review, in Publishers Weekly, says the book addresses `` the gravest, most pressing issues facing doctors today and is <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>'s most skillfully written novel.'' <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, elated, says: `` That means I may be entering a phase of respectability which I've always dreamed of.''
