<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Hit Songs Hurt His Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Songwriter <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Newbury </PERSON> says his career suffered because of two of his best-known compositions: `` American Trilogy'' and `` Just Dropped In -LRB- To See What Condition My Condition Was In -RRB-.'' Both songs, the 48-year-old writer-performer says, boxed him into uncomfortable stereotypes, either as a patriot or a rocker. `` American Trilogy'' was a hit by <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON> in 1973, and `` Just Dropped In'' was recorded by <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> and the First Edition in 1968. `` American Trilogy,'' a medley of `` Dixie,'' `` Battle Hymn of the Republic'' and `` All My Trials,'' has been recorded or performed by dozens of artists. `` It stopped me in my tracks for a few years,'' <PERSON> Newbury </PERSON> said in an interview. `` The only thing I was getting asked to do was sing the national anthem at football games and I did n't like it.'' `` I did <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>'s Fourth of July show. You get a tag and it stuck.'' He says some people still come to his concerts to hear him perform it. `` Hopefully, if I can get them in to see me because of that song, they'll listen to something else I've done. It's the same problem everybody has. For <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, audiences come in to hear their funny stuff but they have a serious side.'' His reputation as a country music songwriter was undermined when `` Just Dropped In'' was taken as a song glorifying drug abuse. `` I was not taken seriously as a country songwriter for a while,'' he recalled. `` It hurt me because of the insanity of the music business. Everyone wanted to put you in a little pigeonhole. `` It was one of the first obvious anti-drug songs, yet it was so controversial that some said it was detrimental. It was about a bad acid trip. All the songs at that time were cloaked in metaphors espousing the glory of hallucinogens. They talked about how wonderful it was and how they open up your mind. It caused me to write it. I knew it was not that way for everyone. It put some people in the toilet.'' <PERSON> Newbury </PERSON>, who now lives in <LOCATION> Vida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, has just released his 14th album, `` <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Newbury </PERSON> in a New Age.'' It's his first LP since 1981 and a kind of greatest hits album. Yes, `` American Trilogy'' is on the disc, along with `` All My Trials,'' `` <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> Mabel Joy'' and others. During his career he's also written `` Sweet Memories,'' a hit by <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, and `` She Even Woke Me Up to Say Goodbye,'' which has been recorded by dozens of performers. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> are just two of the other singers who have recorded his songs. <PERSON> Newbury </PERSON> describes a good song as `` a good story. Something someone can relate to. A lot of songwriters get better as they get older, but they've already written about most of the interesting things in their life that happened when they were young and it was new. `` The whole process that drives you to write is to write that perfect song. No songwriter ever feels he's written that perfect song. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> did it already with ` Beautiful Dreamer' and yet when he died, he had a piece of paper in his pocket that said ` dear hearts and gentle people.' He had already started on another song. `` I think <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON>'s song ` <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>' is a perfect song and I have not heard many perfect songs: ones so finely crafted that you say, ` I ca n't make a change.'''
