<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--MunchausenbyProxy Adv28   07-25 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Munchausen by Proxy, Adv 28,0613</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, July 28, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bizarre Child Abuse Disorder Probably Often Overlooked, Experts
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The boy's mother said he had cystic fibrosis, and so did the lab tests. But the real disease was far more bizarre. And it lay within the mother. No parent could have been more dedicated during the 5-year-old's hospitalizations She stayed with him around the clock and often helped the nurses giving him medications. But, doctors eventually realized, she also altered the boy's stool and perspiration samples to make them consistent with cystic fibrosis She tried to cast doubt on a normal test result by calling the hospital laboratory, giving a false name, and claiming the result was phony. And she tricked a real cystic fibrosis patient into giving her a sputum sample, then submitted the sample to doctors as her son's. Her case is an elaborate example of a psychiatric disorder called `` Munchausen syndrome by proxy,'' a variant of Munchausen syndrome, in which a person fakes disease just to get medical care. It is derived from <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON>, an 18th century German who became well known for elaborate lies. In <LOCATION> Munchausen </LOCATION> by proxy, typically, a mother produces disease or the appearance of disease in her child, then acts like the model of a dedicated and concerned parent. The disorder is probably relatively rare, but `` we suspect it's more common than we think because it's so very difficult to recognize,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Waller </PERSON>, director of child and adolescent psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soutwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> Besides, few doctors are comfortable with confronting a distraught mother who has just spent another sleepless night at the child's bedside and asking `` Are you doing something to that kid?,'' said <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Nadelson </PERSON>, chief of psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Some mothers have slipped their own blood into a child's mouth or urine samples. One was discovered giving a hospitalized infant an enema and putting the fluid in the child's mouth. Another was found to have been giving her child massive doses of a drug to force vomiting. The child died. Just what motivates such behavior is not well understood. It appears to be a way to signal distress, <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> said. And the parent `` gets a lot of reward from being seen as a wonderful, caring parent in her role as helping the child get good medical care.'' <PERSON> Nadelson </PERSON> sees it as a pathological expression of hostility against doctors and society. He considers it an addiction. `` People who do it once will do it again consistently. It's very exciting.'' Usually only one favored child is singled out for what the mother and child consider a game, he said. Treating the disorder is very difficult because people deny that they have the problem, <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> said. There have been anecdotal reports of some treatment successes, said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, clinical instructor of psychiatry at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Nadelson </PERSON> said he believes no treatment really works. Once a case is uncovered, the major goal is to protect the child, <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> said. That sometimes means a court-ordered change in custody. Most children involved in <LOCATION> Munchausen </LOCATION> by proxy are infants or toddlers, but they can occasionally be older children like the boy in the cystic fibrosis scam. Why do the older children go along with it? `` It's the only kind of love the child knows,'' <PERSON> Nadelson </PERSON> said. `` If it's love you're looking for, you'll take it under any circumstances.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
