<HEAD>Pillsbury To Buy Bumble Bee Seafoods, Divest Grain Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it has signed a definitive agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> Bumble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seafoods </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a privately held producer of canned tuna and other seafood. Terms of the agreement were not announced, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said in a prepared statement. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement came three days after H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its agreement to acquire Bumble Bee had been terminated because the federal government was trying to block the deal on antitrust grounds. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> also said Monday it intends to divest its Minneapolis-based grain merchandising division, which operates grain handling and storage facilities primarily in the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The company said it expects to identify a buyer within the next few months. Proceeds from the sale of the grain merchandising division and other sources of internal funding are expected to cover a major portion of the costs associated with the Bumble Bee acquisition, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s statement said. Although grain merchandising has been quite profitable, the company has indicated the division is not part of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term strategic plans, according to the statement `` Today's announcements represent a continuation of our commitment to quality, branded products with unique strengths that provide new growth opportunities for the future,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` We expect Bumble Bee to be a positive contributor to <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings in the first year of operation,'' <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> added. Bumble Bee will continue to operate under its current management as a wholly owned subsidiary with headquarters in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s statement. Bumble Bee, with 1987 sales of $ 265 million, is a top seller of white meat, or albacore, tuna and canned salmon. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, an international food and restaurant organization with fiscal 1988 sales of $ 6.2 billion, includes the <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>'s frozen seafood line which it acquired in 1984 Among the company's other brand names are <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION>, Haagen-Dazs, Burger King, Steak and Ale, and <PERSON> Bennigan </PERSON>'s
