<HEAD>Price Supports, Import Quotas Keep U.S. Sugar Costs High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government sugar policy can be sweet for domestic producers who enjoy high price supports, or bitter for foreign sugar-producing countries whose access to the American market is limited by strict quotas, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report says. `` Although fewer than 1 percent of American farmers grow sugar cane or sugar beets, the commodity is one of the most heavily protected by price supports and import quotas,'' the report said. Those in favor of current policy say federal protection is necessary for the survival of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar industry. Without it, they say it would be impossible for American growers to compete with cheaper sugar from countries that have much lower production costs. Another argument is that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn industry also benefits from higher sugar prices by boosting demand for <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION>, or high fructose corn syrup, in soft drinks and many other food products. But <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts say the other side of the coin includes higher retail prices for American sugar consumers and lost sales _ because of import quotas _ for some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies who depend greatly on sugar as an export commodity. Sugar crops are supported at the equivalent of 18 cents per pound of raw sugar equivalent through `` non-recourse'' loans made by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. It means that if market prices fall below the loan rate, sugar processors can forfeit their collateral without penalty. In that case, the loan obligation is canceled and the CCC takes over ownership of the foreclosed sugar and holds it as surplus. To minimize the risk of forfeiture and to head off large rises in CCC holdings, the market price must be high enough to cover the loan rate, plus interest, plus marketing charges. The desired price is called the Market Stabilization Price, or MSP. For 1987-88, the <ORGANIZATION> MSP </ORGANIZATION> is 21.76 cents per pound. In the first quarter of this year, the duty-paid price of raw sugar delivered to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> averaged 22.03 cents per pound, well above the MSP. Comparatively, the `` world price'' of sugar, based on <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> shipping points, was less than 10 cents per pound. To prevent lower-priced foreign sugar from pulling down the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestic price, import quotas allocated to specific countries have been set each year since 1982. The quotas keep the supply tight enough to maintain prices near the <ORGANIZATION> MSP </ORGANIZATION>, says economist <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` If the estimates of supply and demand are accurate, domestic sugar prices stay high enough to prevent loan forfeitures,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> writes in the forthcoming August issue of Farmline magazine. `` A loan forfeiture presents a surplus and storage problem for the CCC.'' Federal law stipulates that the sugar price support program is to be operated at no net cost to the taxpayers. The cost of the program is basically paid for by American consumers through higher prices for table sugar and products that contain sugar, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. Who benefits? Growers and processing companies, who are guaranteed the support price. Also, indirectly, the corn sweetener industry, which has seen <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> become the dominant sweetener for soft drink manufacturers, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. Glucose and dextrose, also made from corn, for many years had held about 17 percent of the calorie-type sweetener market. But when the new liquid <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> came along, it became the major caloric sweetener used in soft drinks. In 1988, per capita consumption of <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> is forecast at 69.5 pounds per American, 10 percent more than the average for sugar. Foreign manufacturers of products containing sugar, and American consumers of certain imported gourmet food items made from lower-cost foreign sugar, also benefit from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said, the price support program has encouraged greater <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestic sugar production, thereby reducing import requirements, adding to the world export surplus and keeping world prices low. Sugar-importing nations also benefit, he said. By encouraging surpluses and low world sugar prices, the support program of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and some other countries `` create a windfall'' for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the major sugar importers. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said the program also has an effect on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employment. When import quotas shrink, refineries close because they have less foreign raw sugar to process. Since 1982, eight plants have closed, eliminating more than 7,000 jobs, he said. And additional jobs are lost when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers of sugar-containing products reduce output. The highest cost of the sugar program is paid indirectly by sugar exporters, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said. For years, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was the largest importer, with foreign shipments reaching a peak of 6.1 million tons in 1977 and averaging 4.2 million tons a year from 1975 to 1981. In 1988, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sugar import quota initially was about 750,000 tons but was increased Friday to 1.06 million tons. Several bills in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would alter the sugar program. One would reduce the support price to 12 cents per pound from the current level of 18 cents over a period of four crop years. Also, the import quota would be increased by 500,000 tons a year for four years, beginning in 1989. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> said that the lower support `` should lower market prices, and this would probably discourage production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and increase the demand for imported sugar.''
</TEXT>
