<HEAD>Exxon Reports Second-Quarter Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest oil company, today reported a 4 percent increase in second-quarter net income as higher refining and chemicals earnings offset lower exploration and production results. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 1.2 billion, or 90 cents a share, up from net income of $ 1.15 billion, or 81 cents a share in the second quarter of 1987. Revenue for the quarter rose 7 percent to $ 21.63 billion from $ 20.16 billion a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Chairman L.G. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> noted that `` margins were stronger as supply costs dropped and product prices firmed'' during the quarter. He also said increased demand for petroleum products boosted sales volume in both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad. Earnings from exploration and production operations totaled $ 703 million, $ 183 million less than the year-ago period. The company noted that lower crude oil sales to its own refineries as well as to outside customers coupled with higher expenses to offset increased crude production from new and expanded oil fields. The company's chemicals operation reported an $ 89 million increase in earnings to $ 314 million, while higher copper prices helped the coal and minerals unit report net income of $ 8 million, compared with a $ 14 million loss a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> reported corporate and financing charges of $ 172 million, up from $ 24 million a year go. For the first six months, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 2.66 billion, or $ 1.96 a share, up 20 percent from $ 2.22 billion, or $ 1.56 a share in the first half of 1987. Revenue during the period totaled $ 43.63 billion, up 10 percent from revenue of $ 39.6 billion in the year-ago period.
