 Council </ORGANIZATION> decided July 18 to increase production to 1.5 million barrels a day. The U.A.E.'s OPEC-set production quota is 948,000 barrels a day. Crude oil prices have fallen below the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel, even without the increase in production by the <ORGANIZATION> U.A.E. </ORGANIZATION>, largely because of increased non-OPEC production and above-quota production by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members. To enforce the $ 18 price, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> alloted each of its members a quota with total <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production set at 15 million barrels a day. This excludes <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> which refused its allotted quota of 1.54 million barrels a day and has insisted on a quota equal to that of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, its <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war opponent, or 2.37 million barrels a day. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has been producing at a level of about 2.7 million barrels a day.
