<HEAD>Small Wineries A Labor Of Love</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZILLAH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Puryear </PERSON>, the road to joining the <ORGANIZATION> Rothschilds </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Gallos </ORGANIZATION> began with a batch of homemade plum wine. The home brew _ made with directions from a $ 1.99 book, a five-gallon jug and some plastic tubing _ was terrible, said the co-owner of the award-winning Bonair Winery. Things have improved quite a bit since then, and the Puryears are among several small family winemakers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> who compete for shelf space and medals with corporate giants like Chateau Ste. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON>, the state's largest. `` It's so much fun and so romantic,'' <PERSON> Mrs. </PERSON> <PERSON> Puryear </PERSON>, a former social worker in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, said recently. `` This has surpassed my wildest dreams.'' Some of the family winemakers are hobbyists that barely break even, but others are trying hard to make a living at it. `` The glamour fades fast once you get into the business,'' admitted <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, owner of Horizon's Edge Winery in <LOCATION> Zillah </LOCATION>, nestled in the rolling countryside near <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION>. Start-up costs for small wineries average about $ 270,000, and competition is fierce for supermarket and wine list space. About seven of the state's 70 wineries produce under 2,083 cases, or 5,000 gallons, per year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Most of those under 5,000 gallons are family wineries, said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegl </PERSON>, director of the trade By contrast, giants like Chateau Ste. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> produce about 500,000 cases per year and enjoy national distribution. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is the nation's third largest winemaker, after <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, but is far behind <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s 700 wineries. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> winemakers have a history of cooperation, spurring a growth from 11 wineries in 1977 to the present 70. The roots of many wineries are intertwined. For instance, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Conway </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Latah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellars </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, originally moved up from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to help open <PERSON> Worden </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Winery Then he helped start <PERSON> Hogue </PERSON> <PERSON> Cellars </PERSON> of <PERSON> Prosser </PERSON> before securing financial help from the Hogues to launch <LOCATION> Latah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> in 1983. `` The financial help was in exchange for my winemaking at <ORGANIZATION> Hogue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellars </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Conway </PERSON>, whose winery produces 15,000 cases a year. There are many similar stories, because it's an expensive business to get into. `` It's a good way to make a small fortune out of a large one,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who also owns <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winery </ORGANIZATION>, the only one in that state. `` If your total end is to make money, this is not the business to be in,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, one of several alumni of the winemaking program at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Davis </ORGANIZATION> who operate in the state. Horizon's Edge, which opened in 1985 and produces 2,500 cases a year, is approaching $ 100,000 in annual sales, he said. `` I could make more money on the capital in CDs,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> has also worked for Chateau Ste. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Stewart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vineyards </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tucker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellars </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sunnyside </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Blackwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I decided I better carve a niche for myself while I still could,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION>, Mont. Like most of the small wineries, his major market is in state, with many of the sales to visitors in the tasting room. `` Everyone who comes through is having fun,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Puryear </PERSON> of the often raucous mix of visitors to <PERSON> Bonair </PERSON>'s tiny tasting room. `` It's not like buying asparagus at <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION>.'' The tasting room is an important fixture in the small wineries, because up to 80 percent of the product is sold there _ especially by those that do not have wide distribution. `` We get hundreds of people per week here in the summer,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Puryear </PERSON> said, even though the room can hold less than a dozen at one time. `` We get people in here who own wineries in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> or a local who drops by carrying a can of beer,'' she said. Her tasting room has maps of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the world, with pins showing the states and countries of visitors. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> is the only state without a pin. `` The first person from <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> will get a bottle of free wine,'' she said. `` Our choice.'' Owners of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s family wineries, some of which produce considerably more than 5,000 gallons, come from a variety of backgrounds. For instance: _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, owners of <LOCATION> Kiona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vineyards </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, are engineers on the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation, a federal plutonium-making facility _ <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Staton </PERSON>, owner of <LOCATION> Staton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> and a pioneer in wine exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, founded the <PERSON> Wapato </PERSON> winery a decade ago after working as an attorney and as an executive for <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> _ <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Manz </PERSON>, a child psychiatrist and teacher, respectively, began Mountain Dome Winery in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> four years ago They make champagne exclusively and do n't plan to market any of their product until 1992. _ Dr <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sunnyside </LOCATION> established <ORGANIZATION> Stewart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vineyards </ORGANIZATION> in 1983. Ray Small of <PERSON> Walla </PERSON> <PERSON> Walla </PERSON>, half owner of the highly-regarded <ORGANIZATION> Woodward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winery </ORGANIZATION>, says winemaking is more profitable than raising hogs. Small put up the money when his son, <PERSON> Rick </PERSON>, wanted to go into winemaking in 1981 and they produce up to 8,000 gallons per year. The winery is actually a metal building on their farm that originally served as a truck garage and paint shop, he said. `` We've got four or five operations here and some of them are hurting pretty good, like the wheat business and the hog business,'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said. But the winery is `` in the black.'' Winemaking has an attractive, sophisticated image, but <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> owners say the life is n't quite like `` Falcon Crest,'' the television series about intrigues in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s wine country. `` Everybody asks about -LRB- <LOCATION> Falcon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crest </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Puryear </PERSON>. `` I watched one episode and they stuck a body in a wine tank. `` It's not like <LOCATION> Falcon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crest </LOCATION>,'' she said.
