<HEAD>Mellon Announces Refinancing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> today announced a refinancing program of approximately $ 1 billion, including $ 525 million in new equity capital and the sale of lower-quality assets to a new, limited-purpose national bank. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said its lower-quality assets will be reduced by about $ 1 billion. After the sale, <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> said its exposure to the assets will be limited to its $ 100 million investment in the new bank. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said its plan calls for creation of a liquidating national bank, independent of <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, to be called <ORGANIZATION> Grant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. The bank will not take deposits. <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters is on <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said it will create the new bank by distributing common shares of <ORGANIZATION> Grant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to its common shareholders. It said the new bank will acquire <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION>'s low-quality assets from public sale of up to $ 450 million of bonds to be underwritten by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said the sale of assets and the financing for the new bank are expected to occur in the third quarter and are dependent upon approvals from bank regulators.
