<HEAD>Reuters Posts 24.3 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the information services group, said Monday its half-year net profit rose 24.3 percent over a year ago as its financial information and dealing services continued to grow vigorously. However, revenue from trading room systems fell sharply as investment companies implemented sharp cutbacks, <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> said its net profit for the six months ended June 30 came to 63.4 million pounds, or $ 108.4 million, or 15.1 pence a share, compared with 51 million pounds, or 12.2 pence a share, in the same period a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> said its revenue rose 17.7 percent to 471.4 million pounds from 400.4 million pounds. The company did not give out quarterly results. It is not required to release them under British law. The company, which owns the <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency, said revenue growth was curbed by the strength of the pound and a decline in contributions from trading room systems. <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfrew </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION>' managing director and chief executive, said a slowdown in orders for trading room systems was mostly the result of cutbacks in investment firms in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. But orders from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were excellent and orders from continental <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were good, he said.
