<SECOND>BC-Chrysler-Kenosha,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Local 72 Sign Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> signed a contract Monday covering workers affected by the scheduled end of auto production in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> and the closing of the stamping plant in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> vice president and director of its <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> department, said he hoped there would be `` life after current production'' which is scheduled to end in December at the former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>. `` We hope this will not be the end of this operation. It is our hope that it does continue,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. The agreement covers 5,500 workers in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> and 450 at the stamping plant, which already has closed. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said he was particularly happy about the commitment in the contract calling for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> to pay back AMC profit-sharing that <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> had promised members of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> locals 72 and 75 in exchange for concessions. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> acquired the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> car-making plant and the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> stamping operation when it bought <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> initially planned to keep the plant open for several years, but then announced it did not need the production capability. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, vice president for human resources at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, also cited provisions in the pact calling for worker benefits to continue for up to two years after the layoffs and to allow special early retirements for some senior workers. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the decision to stop building cars in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> as of December stands. When asked if there was any chance of it continuing into 1989, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said, `` I would suggest that the answer is no to that.'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the company projects that the produced in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> at a separate plant that employs about 800 workers will be needed through 1992. But he said it is possible that plant could close before that. `` However, it certainly is not likely,'' he said.
