<FIRST>r f AM-StickierStamps Bjt   07-25 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stickier Stamps, Bjt,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference To Debate Philatelic Problem: Why Won't Stamps Stick?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A think tank has been given 10 months to answer a question that has concerned consumers and plagued philatelists since the dawn of postal automation: Why wo n't stamps stick? <ORGANIZATION> Battelle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which recently received a $ 700,000 contract from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service, convenes a meeting here Thursday in hopes of making a sticky situation stickier, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON>, general manager of the stamp division of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. About 100 representatives of adhesive manufacturers and paper companies expected to attend the one-day meeting will be asked to share their thoughts and, in some cases, their secret formulas. `` I do n't think $ 700,000 is too much to pay for a stamp that sticks,'' he said in a telephone interview. `` Compare that to the fact that stamps are an $ 8 billion-a-year business.'' The Columbus-based institute is trying to find a perfect stamp glue _ one that not only will keep stamp and envelope together from the point of origin to destination, but will taste a little better, <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> said. `` The public insists that it at least, if it ca n't stick, not taste so bad,'' he said. `` The problem is finding a consensus on what tastes good. Some people like liver, others do n't. So it's got to be something that may not taste great, and may not taste like anything at all.'' He said consumers have repeatedly suggested more flavorful glues that taste like cherry, vanilla and vodka. `` Oh, they have suggested it, but I hardly think vodka would be appropriate,'' he said, laughing. `` No, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>, we're not planning on that at all.'' Neither <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Battelle </PERSON> consider the issue a laughing matter. `` Sure, people giggle. But it's not very funny to us. It's very important to us, and to the people who want their letters to reach their destinations,'' <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Battelle </PERSON>'s task will not be easy. `` Do you have any idea how many adhesives there are in the world?'' he said. The Postal Service uses three kinds of adhesives now, which <PERSON> McDowell </PERSON> describes as `` shiny, not shiny and halfway in between.'' He could not estimate how many stamps are lost in transit every year, but said the problem has gotten worse since the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> began to automate in the early 1970s. `` Before then, when it was manual, the impact to a stamp was like a car hitting a brick wall at 5 mph. Now, it's like a car hitting a brick wall at 60 mph. Because these machines accelerate and decelerate so fast, when the envelope stops, the stamp does n't want to,'' he said Slowing the machines wo n't fix the problem, he said. The rising volume of mailed items means the system will have to speed up. About 35 million stamped items move through the system every year. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philatelic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of stamp collectors, has argued that not only is the adhesive not sticky enough, it also eats through the paper, which decreases a stamp's value One philatelist does not agree that a new glue is needed. M.W. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Topical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philatelic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> says the glue is not the culprit. He blames the disappearing stamp dilemma on human error and sorting machines that are not stamp-friendly. `` I'm in this business 40 years and I just do n't see the non-sticky problem. If they fall off sometimes, it's not the glue. People are n't licking them enough, the envelope maybe has some dust on it. I think the real problem is the machines at the post office,'' he said.
</TEXT>
