<FIRST>a f AM-Japan-BuyingLuxury Adv28   07-25 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Buying Luxury, Adv 28,0630</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs July 28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Beginning to Spend their Yen on Luxury Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese are breaking with a tradition of frugality to bring some luxury into their lives _ big cars, European furniture, diamond jewelry. The government has been urging them to spend the yen they ordinarily put in the bank, in hopes of spurring the domestic economy. Analysts say skyrocketing property values, easy credit, price stability and the yen's rise in value are generating a fast-growing market for luxury goods _ a turnaround from three years of slumping consumption when the surging yen subdued the export-driven economy. `` Selling well are expensive and luxurious durable goods such as large-size TV sets, refrigerators, furniture and dining ware imported from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mitsuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirose </PERSON> of the Sales Promotion Division at <ORGANIZATION> Matsuya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a major department store on <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s bustling <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION>. A recent <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> report called brisk personal buying a `` key element'' of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s current economic success. The government has cut income taxes and launched a 5-trillion-yen -LRB- $ 40 billion -RRB- public spending program, spurring housing starts. The bank cut its discount rate to a record low 2.5 percent, and the public <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> trimmed more than a percentage point off its interest rate, currently 4.35 percent. Consumer demand as measured by department store sales jumped 8.2 percent in April from a year earlier, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Total sales by 254 major department stores last year rose an average 4.7 percent every month, the association said. And the gross national product, which measures total output of goods and services, grew at an annualized rate of 11.3 percent in the first quarter of this year, figures from the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> indicate. `` People regard expensive, new products as a means of being somewhat different from others,'' said <PERSON> Takayuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Ikeda </PERSON>, manager of the Consumer Electronics Product Division at <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In 1985 the company began marketing its 37-inch color television set, the industry equivalent of 35-inch American models, for 478,000 yen -LRB- $ 3,825 -RRB-. `` At first we never thought a large-sized TV with a built-in picture tube would be accepted in Japanese homes, which some Europeans have ridiculed as ` rabbit hutches','' <PERSON> Ikeda </PERSON> said in an interview, `` but the opposite is true. People have realized that the larger the TV screen, the more fun they can have, the more feeling of real ambience.'' Japanese bought 9.6 million color TV sets last year, 20 percent of which measured 22 inches or larger, up 12 percent from 1986, according to industry figures. Automakers are benefiting from the Japanese who now want bigger, more expensive cars. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in April sold 14,673 of its large-size, 4.6-million-yen -LRB- $ 37,000 -RRB-, top-of-the-line Crown models _ a 92.5-percent jump from a year earlier. `` People's sense of money has become accentuated,'' said <PERSON> Isao </PERSON> <PERSON> Takayama </PERSON>, chief of the jewelry division at the swank <ORGANIZATION> Mitsukoshi </ORGANIZATION> department stores. `` Several years ago you could buy a house for 50 to 60 million yen. Now it costs up to 500 million yen -LRB- $ 4 million -RRB-. It tends to dull people's sense of money.'' Reflecting a demand for expensive ornaments, imports of polished diamonds rose 61.6 percent to 1.06 million carats in the first four months of this year over last year, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Takayama </PERSON> said the hottest items are diamond rings priced at 2 million yen -LRB- $ 16,000 -RRB-. `` Nowadays customers come in asking to see diamonds of about 100 million yen -LRB- $ 228,000 -RRB-,'' he said. `` Four or five years ago, that was the stuff of dreams.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thursday AMs July 28</NOTE>
