<FIRST>u f AM-JapanWorries Bjt   07-25 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan Worries, Bjt,0694</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Japanese Economy Sending Confused Signals, Economists Say</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> opened last Tuesday, grim-faced Japanese businessmen began filing into the lobby of <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> shopping district to track the market's performance Their faces grew grim as a retreat that began the previous day in response to a jump in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar's value quickly turned into a rout. Before it was over, the market's barometer, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues, had lost 513.09 points, its biggest loss of the year. After a brief rebound at mid-week, the decline resumed, stripping more than 600 points from the average by week's end. On Monday, the market rose 76.55 points at the opening bell, then slumped again to finish down 117.81 at 27,183.53. While the declines pale in comparison to the calamitous plunge of last October when <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> markets set off a worldwide stock market panic, they are worrisome nonetheless. Some Japanese economists view the latest decline as a warning shot for the high-flying Japanese economy, and they caution that the next `` Black Monday'' could be precipitated here. `` I think these are continuing signs of confusion over the direction of the economy in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON>, senior economist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` These are warning signals, and people are nervous.'' Market analysts blamed the wave of selling on market shifts, from steel and shipbuilding shares to electronics. <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said investors are trying to take their money into more stable stocks, so they have a better chance of selling if the market falls. `` When people have their eyes on the fire exit, they buy those stocks,'' he said. The root of the concern appears to be the recent surge in the dollar's value, which has moved above the psychologically important level of 130 yen after a long decline. Some experts here also view the recent increase in American interest rates as a precursor of higher Japanese rates. The boost in the dollar sprang partly from an improvement in American trade statistics, which show the imbalance between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports and exports is shrinking. That shift _ while good news for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> industry _ threatens to divert the lifeblood of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s boom, which has drawn its strength from a steady stream of exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeing the high side of this process,'' <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said of the changing trade relationship. `` But its trading partners are beginning to feel the heat. This is now beginning to show a strain on the Japanese economy.'' <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said there was so much growth last year that if the Japanese economy had zero growth in 1988, it would still be 3.4 percent above a year ago. The Japanese government's leading index of economic indicators fell two months in a row, in March and April. A decline two months in a row typically has meant a recession in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> within four to eight months. Industrial production was down 3.8 percent for April and May, which portends zero or negative growth for the second quarter. Housing starts have been falling rapidly, following a boom last year that raised real estate prices and cooled the enthusiasm of prospective home buyers. The gloomy view is far from universal, however. Last week, a group of 21 Japanese financial institutions issued a glowing report on the state of the economy, saying growth through the fiscal year was expected to be 4.4 percent to 5.4 percent. <PERSON> Teruhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mano </PERSON>, an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, said the recent market swings are `` merely an adjustment, not an indicator of recession.'' He also takes issue with the housing slowdown, which he says is merely a reaction against prices that were too high to begin with. `` The dollar went up, and the market went down,'' he said of the stock market drop. `` Our economy is reacting to the capitalistic system. It shows it is working well.''
</TEXT>
