<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, enjoying higher than expected orders for two new desktop computers, Monday reported a 91 percent jump in net income for the second quarter. Sales for the second quarter increased 71 percent compared to the same period a year ago. The Houston-based firm on June 20 began volume shipments of two new desktop computers and were met with stronger initial dealer demand than any other product in the company's history, officials said. `` Our solid second-quarter financial results reflect continued strong worldwide demand for our high-performance, industry-standard products,'' said <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Canion </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer. Part of the increase was a non-recurring, pretax gain of nearly $ 10 million that resulted from an increase in the carrying value of the company's investment in <ORGANIZATION> Conner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peripherals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which was offered publicly for the first time during the quarter. During the second quarter of 1988, net income rose to $ 59 million, or $ 1.45 per share, on sales of $ 457 million from $ 31 million, or 80 cents per share on sales of $ 268 million a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>'s gain from the <ORGANIZATION> Conner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peripherals </ORGANIZATION> public offering increased earnings per share by about 15 cents in the period, officials said. Net income for the first six months of 1988 was $ 105 million, or $ 2.66 per share, compared with $ 51 million, or $ 1.36 per share, in the first half of 1987. Sales totaled $ 896 million up from $ 478 million. The company established a subsidiary in <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> during the second quarter, bringing to 43 the number of countries where <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> computers are available.
