<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Falls In Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar climbed higher at the end of trading in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> Monday, despite central bank intervention to hold it down, dealers said. Gold prices fell more than $ 7 an ounce in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on what dealers said profit-taking after last week's advance. Dollar trading was initially hectic Monday, dealers said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency jumped sharply in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, but was brought lower when the West German central bank intervened to sell dollars, they said. `` At present levels, there is new demand,'' a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> dealer said. Dealers said they believed the dollar hit bottom late last week and is heading for higher ground again. Some dealers in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said the central bank may have intervened partly to prop up the mark against the British pound, which also strengthened against the West German currency Monday. Dealers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said the pound continued to be buoyed by the market's belief that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates are unlikely to come down in the near future, putting the brakes on inflation. But the British currency fell against the dollar. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound was quoted at $ 1.7265, compared with $ 1.7405 Friday. Other late dollar rates, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.8452 West German marks, up from 1.8265; 1.5345 Swiss francs, up from 1.5175; 6.2215 French francs, up from 6.1630; 2.0745 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0615; 1,359.50 Italian lire, up from 1,353.75; 1.2075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1983. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar fell 0.28 yen to a closing 131.80. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 132.08 yen. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 434.75 a troy ounce, compared with late Friday's $ 442. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was lower, closing at a bid $ 437.50, compared with $ 442.50 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 34 cents to close at a bid $ 444.28. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 7.60 a troy ounce, compared with Friday's $ 7.76.
