rformance at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, others suggested <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> merely wanted to run his own show. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a 22-year veteran of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement that `` <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is a terrific company with fine businesses and excellent people.'' `` I'm looking forward to leading this company aggressively with its exciting and challenging opportunities,'' he said. The 65-year-old <PERSON> Spoor </PERSON> returned to the helm at <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> after the ouster of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Spoor </PERSON> had groomed as his successor and who presided over <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s first earnings decline in 16 years. <PERSON> Spoor </PERSON> had run the company from 1973 through 1985. Speculation had been swirling on Wall Street recently that despite its difficulties, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> might be a takeover target. But analysts are divided as to how attractive a takeover candidate <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> may be. <PERSON> Carnes </PERSON>, for instance, said <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> had `` too many wrecks in the ditch right now.'' Some people have said the Burger King chain could fetch as much as $ 1.5 billion if it were spun off as a separate company, but <PERSON> Carnes </PERSON> estimated the chain would bring only about $ 900 million because it was at least two years away from a turnaround. <ORGANIZATION> Pilip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Hamish </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> issued a statement praising <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s tenure at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> and said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s position would not be filled. <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>