<HEAD>FCC Threatens US Sprint With Sanctions Over Consumer Billing
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has indicated it may fine <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> unless the long-distance phone company does a better job responding to consumer billing complaints. Customer complaints about inaccurate, incomplete and late bills have plagued the nation's third-largest long-distance company since it was formed in July 1986 and have contributed to its losses. In a letter last week to <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Snedaker </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said it was concerned about the volume of billing complaints it has received from <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> customers and the company's `` inadequate and inaccurate responses.'' While other carriers have experienced billing complaints, they usually correct the problem within two to three months, said the letter, signed by <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s top telephone official. `` In <LOCATION> US </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>'s case, however, various billing and related problems have been occurring for well over a year,'' <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said. `` These problems have been compounded by <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>'s apparent inability to promptly rectify complaints either when a customer directly contacts <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> or when the customer contacts the commission.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> gave <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> 20 days to explain the procedures it has in place to investigate complaints forwarded by the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> and what steps it intends to respond to these complaints within the 30 days required by law. <LOCATION> US </LOCATION> Sprint officials had no comment Monday on the letter. Previously, the company has blamed the billing errors on computer problems and has said it was bringing the foulups under control. <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogt </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s telephone enforcement unit, said the agency received 1,821 complaints against <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> between Oct. 1, 1986, and July 14, but said `` we would be seeing the tip of the iceberg of what <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> sees'' in complaints directly from customers. During the same period, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> received 1,114 complaints against <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and 494 against <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, he said. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T, the nation's largest long-distance company, says it serves about 70 percent of the interstate long-distance market, while <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> claims about 10 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> about 6 percent. <PERSON> Vogt </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, if not satisfied with <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to make timely responses to complaints, could fine the company as much as $ 2,000 per violation, up to a total of $ 20,000. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced it was selling most of its 50 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> to its partner in the venture, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> will raise its stake in <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> to 80.1 percent early next year <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 138 million in the first quarter of 1988 after racking up losses of $ 800 million last year. The two parents have shared those losses equally.
