<HEAD>Manville Reports Second Quarter Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that its after-tax profit slumped 19.5 percent in the second quarter because of special charges related to asbestos clean-up costs and the shutdown of a plywood operation. The building materials company said its net profit totaled $ 33.1 million, or $ 1.12 a share, in the April-June period, compared with earnings of $ 41.1 million, or $ 1.45 a share, in the same 1987 quarter. Revenue rose 8.3 percent to $ 561 million from $ 517.8 million. For the first six months, profit fell 18.1 percent to $ 68.8 million, or $ 2.35 a share, from $ 84 million, or $ 2.97 a share, in 1987. Revenue rose 10.8 percent to $ 1.1 billion from $ 992.9 million. <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> said the $ 13.9 million after-tax charge primarily covered removing asbestos from company property. It also included a provision for the closing of a plywood operation at <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION>'s facility in <LOCATION> Huttig </LOCATION>, Ark Net earnings for the first six months of 1987 included a one-time gain of $ 9 million from the sale of two real estate joint ventures. `` While our overall operating performance remains strong, we continued to experience severe competition in most construction markets during the second quarter,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer. <ORGANIZATION> Manville </ORGANIZATION> filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code on Aug. 26, 1982. The company's reorganization plan was approved by the bankruptcy court judge on Dec. 22, 1986, and upheld by the 2nd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this past March. An appeal of the approval is now