<HEAD>Court Judgment Reduces Eaton Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its second-quarter profit fell by 29.5 percent from a year earlier, due mainly to a charge taken to reflect a $ 17.6 million court judgment against the company. <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> posted after-tax profits of $ 46.6 million, or $ 1.87 a share, down from $ 66.1 million, or $ 2.31 a share during the same period last year. The latest quarter's earnings also included net income of $ 700,000 from discontinued operations. The year-earlier quarter included a $ 7 million gain from the sale of the company's polymer products division. Quarterly sales were $ 886.3 million, up from $ 807.7 million during the same period last year. The company said its net earnings from continuing operations rose 2.9 percent during the period, to $ 63.6 million from $ 61.8 million. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last week affirmed a 1983 jury award of $ 17.6 million against <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> stemming from a 1976 lawsuit that PKL Liquidating Trust filed against <ORGANIZATION> Cutler-Hammer </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a company <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> bought in 1978. The lawsuit concerned PKL's minority shareholding in <LOCATION> Macrodata </LOCATION>, which merged with <ORGANIZATION> Cutler-Hammer </ORGANIZATION> in 1977. <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> said it is appealing the ruling to the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> makes automotive, industrial, commercial and defense products including truck transmissions, engine components, electrical equipment and controls. For the first half of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Eaton </ORGANIZATION> reported net income, including discontinued operations, of $ 106.9 million, or $ 4.28 a share, down 15.3 percent from the $ 126.3 million, or $ 4.33 a share, in the same period last year. Earnings on continuing operations were up 6.7 percent to $ 123.7 million, or from $ 115.9 million in the first half of 1987. Sales for the first six months of this year were $ 1.75 billion, up from $ 1.58 billion a year earlier.
