<HEAD>Guild Drops Opposition to JOA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Newspaper Guild of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, the only union at the city's two largest daily newspapers, on Monday dropped opposition to a proposal to partially merge the two publications, a union official said. The decision came during a union meeting Monday morning and after the union received concessions from the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> during labor negotiations in three areas, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kummer </PERSON>, administrator of Local 22 of The Newspaper Guild. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to better pension language, a retraining program for employees laid off if the proposed joint operating agreement is approved and a cap on the number of Guild members subject to such layoff. <ORGANIZATION> Knight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement Monday welcoming the Guild's decision. `` The Guild thus joins the other five unions which originally intervened in this proceeding, in urging approval of the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION>,'' the statement said. The Free Press and the Detroit News asked the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 for an exemption in antitrust law allowing them to merge their business, advertising and circulation departments. Editorial departments would remain separate. A spokesman for Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who must rule on such exemptions, has said he plans to decide on the <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> sometime before he leaves office Aug. 15. A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> staff report and an administrative law judge, who held heari