<HEAD>Kimberly-Clark Profit Up 19.5 Percent In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its second quarter net income was up by 19.5 percent from the same period last year. The household, paper and personal care products company posted a profit of $ 100.1 million, or $ 1.25 per share, compared with $ 83.8 million, or 96 cents per share, in second quarter 1987. Sales during the quarter rose to $ 1.34 billion from $ 1.22 billion. For the first six months of the year, net income rose to $ 193.4 million, or $ 2.41 per share, from $ 158.9 million, or $ 1.76 per share, in the same period of last year. First half sales rose to $ 2.6 billion from $ 2.4 billion a year earlier. Company officials said about 60 percent of the increase in earnings came from outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where increased competition resulted in increased advertising and promotional expenses. The company also said its board of directors had adopted a shareholder rights takeover defense, in order to discourage potential unwanted buyout overtures. <PERSON> Darwin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Kimberly-Clark </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said he knew of no buyout offers during the second quarter.
